EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure developing south of Long Island and moving northeastward across southern New England brought six to twelve inches of snow to northern Massachusetts and southern New Hampshire with lesser amounts elsewhere in the region. Much of this fell during the evening rush hour impacting travel.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Eight to twelve inches of snow fell across eastern Hillsborough County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moving off the mid-Atlantic coast intensified as it moved northeastward over Nantucket. This spread heavy snow across all of southern New England.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six to twelve inches of snow fell across eastern Hillsborough County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure brought a brief period of heavy snowfall to southern New Hampshire.  This snowfall was heaviest across eastern Hillsborough County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four to eight inches of snow fell across eastern Hillsborough County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong coastal storm moved up the east coast and over Nantucket bringing a heavy wet snow to much of the area. This resulted in tree damage and scattered power outages across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six to eight inches of snow fell across eastern Hillsborough County.  The heavy wet snow brought down trees, limbs, and wires in Merrimack and Nashua.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A significant winter storm brought six to twelve inches of snow across much of southern New England. Lesser amounts fell east of the Interstate 95 corridor where snow changed to rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Five to eight inches of snow fell across eastern Hillsborough County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong cold air advection behind a mid level low resulted in strong winds at the surface. This caused some wind damage mainly across eastern Hillsborough County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Automated Surface Observation System at Manchester Airport (KMHT) recorded sustained winds of 38 mph and gusts to 50 mph.  A tree and wires were downed onto Spring Street in Hillsborough.  A tree and wires were downed blocking the intersection of Brown Avenue and Faith Lane in Manchester.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A significant, rapidly developing coastal storm moved southeast of Southern New England bringing heavy snow, bitter cold temperatures, and strong winds to all of the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six to nine inches of snow fell across eastern Hillsborough County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low level jet coupled with the advance of a cold front resulted in windy conditions at the surface. This led to some wind damage particularly across eastern Hillsborough County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Automated Surface Observation System at Manchester Airport (KMHT) recorded wind gusts of 42 mph. A tree was downed onto Burns Hill Road in Hudson, closing the road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large ocean storm intensified very quickly off the east coast of the United States. This storm brought strong winds to parts of New Hampshire.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree and wires were downed on Chestnut Street in Nashua.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An intensifying coastal low pressure system moved up the coast from North Carolina, crossing the benchmark (40 N/70 W) southeast of Nantucket. This storm brought strong to damaging winds to much of New England. Little precipitation was received with this storm, with less than 1 to 2 inches of snow reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree and wires were downed on Dublin Avenue in Nashua. In Merrimack, a tree and wires were downed on Wire Road between Mallard Point and Ichabod Roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm southerly flow allowed for temperatures to reach well into the 80s to near 90 on Wednesday, July 2nd.  In addition, it was rather humid with dewpoints nearing 70 degrees.  With the warm and humid conditions in place, the atmosphere became quite unstable during the afternoon and evening hours.||Well ahead of a cold front, a surface trough was in place across upstate New York.  This caused thunderstorms to develop during the afternoon hours.  Many of these storms became severe, producing wind damage to trees and power lines.  A few storms also contained large hail.  In addition, the very humid air mass in place gave the storms the capability of producing very heavy rainfall in a short period of time.  This allowed for a few of the storms to produce flash flooding in urban areas, such as around the Capital Region.  ||In addition, these storms produced a significant amount of cloud to ground lightning.  Several highway employees were struck by lightning in Rotterdam during a thunderstorm, but luckily escaped serious injury.  ||Although most of the storm ended by the late afternoon hours, a few additional severe storms during during the evening across the western Adirondacks and western Mohawk Valley.  These storms ended by the late evening hours, as nocturnal influences helped wane the development of additional thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous tree limbs were reported down due to thunderstorm winds in Ravena.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front with a wave of low pressure moving along it into northern Ohio produced strong storms with heavy rain on July 27, 2014. High moisture content over the region, as indicated by dew points in the upper 60s, combined with some upslope and lake enhancement to cause flash floods. Some of the stronger storms produced strong damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Starting around 520 PM on the evening of the 27th storms associated with a cold front moving through the region produced torrential rain over the Middlefield area. Between 545 and 715 PM 4.13 of rain fell as reported by the CoCoRaHS observer in Middlefield. It was this heavy rain that caused the Tare Creek to overcome it's banks and flood a retirement community and an apartment complex. This was the first ever reported incident of the creek flooding the retirement home which was built in 1965. The flood waters filled the basement with seven feet of water and resulted in evacuations. Further downstream sat an apartment complex where the Fire Department performed water rescues of 8 residents. The flood waters were estimated at eight inches deep in the apartments. An additional 0.9 of rain fell between 8 PM and 8 AM but no additional flash flooding resulted. Numerous homes in the community had flooded basements.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm southerly flow allowed for temperatures to reach well into the 80s to near 90 on Wednesday, July 2nd.  In addition, it was rather humid with dewpoints nearing 70 degrees.  With the warm and humid conditions in place, the atmosphere became quite unstable during the afternoon and evening hours.||Well ahead of a cold front, a surface trough was in place across upstate New York.  This caused thunderstorms to develop during the afternoon hours.  Many of these storms became severe, producing wind damage to trees and power lines.  A few storms also contained large hail.  In addition, the very humid air mass in place gave the storms the capability of producing very heavy rainfall in a short period of time.  This allowed for a few of the storms to produce flash flooding in urban areas, such as around the Capital Region.  ||In addition, these storms produced a significant amount of cloud to ground lightning.  Several highway employees were struck by lightning in Rotterdam during a thunderstorm, but luckily escaped serious injury.  ||Although most of the storm ended by the late afternoon hours, a few additional severe storms during during the evening across the western Adirondacks and western Mohawk Valley.  These storms ended by the late evening hours, as nocturnal influences helped wane the development of additional thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were downed and lying across a road due to thunderstorm winds in Atwood.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A hot and humid air mass was in place on Tuesday, July 1st, which allowed for the atmosphere to become quite unstable.  A weak surface boundary moved east across upstate New York during the evening hours, which caused a broken line of showers and thunderstorms to develop.  One of these thunderstorms grew tall enough to become severe, producing wind damage across parts of southern Saratoga County.  The showers and thunderstorms moved eastward and weakened by the late evening hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three trees were reportedly downed by thunderstorm winds 5 miles north-northwest of Burnt Hills.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm and humid air mass was in place over the region on Thursday, July 3rd.  As a strong cold front approached from the west, a broken line of thunderstorms developed over central New York and moved eastward during the afternoon hours.  Aided by powerful winds aloft, the storms moved from west to east over the region between the late afternoon and early evening hours.  Many of the storms produced strong winds, causing damage to trees and power lines over much of the region.  The most concentrated damage occurred from one particularly severe thunderstorm, which caused intense damage between West Winfield in Herkimer County towards Minden in Montgomery County.  A National Weather Service Storm Survey determined a series of microbursts produced wind damage up to 100 MPH in these areas.  A few of the storms also produced large hail as well.||As the cold front moved through the area by later in the evening, the storms moved east of the region and the threat for severe weather ended.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were reported to be downed by thunderstorm winds in the town of Norway.  One of the trees was reported to be on a house.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very warm and humid air mass was in place over the region on Tuesday, July 8th.   The region was ahead of a strong cold front that was moving eastward from the Great Lakes Region.  Aided by a strong jet streak aloft and a potent upper level shortwave trough, the cold front triggered a line of thunderstorms that produced damaging winds across western and central New York.||The line of thunderstorms reached eastern New York during the evening hours.  It continued to produce strong winds, which caused damage across the Adirondacks and Mohawk Valley and eventually into the Saratoga area, Capital Region and Hudson Valley as well. Many trees and power lines were downed across Herkimer County.  In addition, a weak, brief tornado also occurred in the southeastern Adirondacks in North Creek.   The line of thunderstorms moved eastward and weakened as they reached the border with New England by the late evening hours.  As a result, the threat for severe weather ended.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were downed in Dolgeville due to thunderstorm winds.

The line of thunderstorms moved eastward and weakened as they reached the border with New England by the late evening hours.  As a result, the threat for severe weather ended.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were reported down in Napanoch due to thunderstorm winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm and humid air mass was in place across southern Vermont on the afternoon of Monday, July 7th.  A cluster of showers and thunderstorms moved from upstate New York into southern Vermont during the mid afternoon hours.  These thunderstorms had previously weakened, but were still associated with very strong winds aloft.  As these thunderstorms interacted with the high terrain of the southern Green Mountains, they produced gusty winds.  These winds caused damage to trees and power lines near Readsboro. The thunderstorm continued eastward towards the Connecticut River Valley, but did not produce any additional severe weather before exiting the state to the east.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Many trees and power lines were reported down near the intersection of Bosley Hill Road and Tunnel Street in Readsboro to thunderstorms winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm and humid air mass was in place over the region on Thursday, July 3rd.  As a strong cold front approached from the west, a broken line of thunderstorms developed over central New York and moved eastward during the afternoon hours.  Aided by powerful winds aloft, the storms moved from west to east over the region between the late afternoon and early evening hours.  Many of the storms produced strong winds, causing damage to trees and power lines over much of the region.  The most concentrated damage occurred from one particularly severe thunderstorm, which caused intense damage between West Winfield in Herkimer County towards Minden in Montgomery County.  A National Weather Service Storm Survey determined a series of microbursts produced wind damage up to 100 MPH in these areas.  A few of the storms also produced large hail as well.||As the cold front moved through the area by later in the evening, the storms moved east of the region and the threat for severe weather ended.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were reported down due to thunderstorm winds on State Route 22 in Ancram.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Although the day began with clouds, breaks in the clouds during the afternoon hours allowed the atmosphere to become unstable over northwestern Connecticut. As a surface trough and upper level shortwave approached from the Great Lakes, thunderstorms broke out over eastern New York. Although the thunderstorms weren't overly tall, strong winds aloft allowed the storms to rotate and produce damaging wind gusts, mainly to trees, across Ulster and Dutchess Counties during the evening hours. As these thunderstorms moved into northwestern Connecticut, one of the storms produced wind damage across Litchfield County.  With the loss of daytime heating, thunderstorms weakened and ended by the late-evening hours, ending the threat for severe weather.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was reported down due to thunderstorm winds in East Canaan.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A hot and humid air mass was in place on Wednesday, July 23rd, allowing the atmosphere to become quite unstable.  As a cold front approached from the west, clusters of thunderstorms developed during the afternoon and early evening hours.  Some of these thunderstorms became severe, producing damaging winds and large hail.  Thunderstorms moved east and weakened by the late evening hours, as the cold front crossed the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were reported down on Pinot Ranch Road in Valatie due to thunderstorm winds.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A large 100 foot pine tree was struck by lightning at the Saratoga Race Course in Saratoga Springs.  Pieces of the downed tree destroyed about a dozen picnic tables and the Dogs and Brews tent.  Some of the debris was scattered nearly 100 feet away from the tree that was struck.  The lightning strike occurred about 20 minutes after the last race of the day had ended and most people had already left the area.  As a result, no injuries were reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving cold front approached the region on Tuesday, July 15th.  With a very moist and tropical air mass in place, repeated bands of showers and thunderstorms developed ahead of the boundary.  These showers and thunderstorms produced very heavy downpours in a short period of time, with up to two inches of rain falling over eastern Ulster County.  As a result of the heavy rainfall, flash flooding occurred in the Woodstock area, causing several roads to be closed.  The roads eventually reopened once showers ended and the water receded.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rainfall from thunderstorms caused flash flooding in Woodstock. Macdaniel Road was closed due to high water.

For the third day in a row, thunderstorms produced reports of wind damage across the region, with a few reports of large hail as well, as the storms moved from west to east.  ||The threat for storms ended during the evening hours, as the cold front moved across the area and into New England.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A large tree fell and knocked over a fence on New Scotland Avenue in Albany due to thunderstorm winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very warm and humid air mass was in place over the region on Tuesday, July 8th.   The region was ahead of a strong cold front that was moving eastward from the Great Lakes Region.  Aided by a strong jet streak aloft and a potent upper level shortwave trough, the cold front triggered a line of thunderstorms that produced damaging winds across western and central New York.||The line of thunderstorms reached eastern New York during the evening hours.  It continued to produce strong winds, which caused damage across the Adirondacks and Mohawk Valley and eventually into the Saratoga area, Capital Region and Hudson Valley as well. Many trees and power lines were downed across Herkimer County.  In addition, a weak, brief tornado also occurred in the southeastern Adirondacks in North Creek.   The line of thunderstorms moved eastward and weakened as they reached the border with New England by the late evening hours.  As a result, the threat for severe weather ended.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wires were reported down and across Roche Drive in the town of Ancram due to thunderstorm winds.

Winds estimated at more than 60 mph downed many trees at a campground between Lake Milton and Berlin Lake.  Several people were briefly trapped in the campground because trees blocked several roads.  No injuries were reported.

Winds estimated at more than 60 mph downed many trees at a campground between Lake Milton and Berlin Lake.  Several people were briefly trapped in the campground because trees blocked several roads.  No injuries were reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front with a wave of low pressure moving along it into northern Ohio produced strong storms with heavy rain on July 27, 2014. High moisture content over the region, as indicated by dew points in the upper 60s, combined with some upslope and lake enhancement to cause flash floods. Some of the stronger storms produced strong damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain fell along and just south of the Ashtabula/Trumbull County line. Most of the rain fell over the Stratton and Maple Creek basins, tributaries to the Pymatuning Creek, near Kinsman. The creek overflowed it's banks and washed out portions of Kinsman-Pymatuning Road between Route 7 and Delin Thomas Road. The local golf course sustained significant damage to culverts and roads caused by the flood waters.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cool airmass with high pressure was over the Great Lakes on the morning of July 10. A waterspout developed on a land breeze north of Toledo in Maumee Bay.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The media reported a waterspout north of Toledo in Maumee Bay.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong thunderstorm moved across Erie County, Pennsylvania as a cold front moved across the area. The thunderstorm caused many downed trees and was accompanied by quarter size hail on Old Frisbeetown Rd east of Mill Village.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter reported quarter size hail on Old Frisbeetown Road east of Mill Village.  Numerous trees and power lines were also brought down from strong thunderstorm winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front moved across upstate New York during the early afternoon on Thursday, July 31st.  Ahead of this boundary, the atmosphere was warm and unstable.  A line of showers and thunderstorms developed along the boundary and quickly moved eastward.  One area of the thunderstorms became severe across Saratoga County, producing damaging wind gusts and small hail.  ||The thunderstorms raced eastward into New England by the mid-afternoon, ending the threat for severe weather.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple trees were reported down in Malta due to thunderstorm winds.  Some of the downed trees fell on cars as well.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The combination of an approaching cold front and potent upper level jet allowed for some thunderstorms to develop in the late afternoon and early evening hours on Friday, May 30th.  A few of these thunderstorms became severe, producing hail to the size of quarters and wind damage to trees and power lines.  Thunderstorm activity waned by later in the evening, as the front moved to the east of the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported by a member of the public 1 mile west of West Middleburgh.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Ahead of a slow moving cold front, a southerly flow transported plenty of moisture into the region during the day on Tuesday, June 3rd.  With a moist and unstable air mass in place, plenty of slow moving showers and thunderstorms developed ahead of the approaching boundary.  Some of these thunderstorms produced very heavy rain in a short period of time.  This led to some flash flooding, especially in urban and poor drainage areas.  In addition, a few of the thunderstorms also produced strong wind gusts, which caused damage to trees and power lines.  By the late evening, the threat for thunderstorms ended, as the frontal boundary pushed through and less humid air moved into the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nickel size hail was reported during a thunderstorm in Livingston.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm and humid air mass was in place on the evening of Tuesday, June 17th.   A strong cold front moved across the region from west to east between late in the evening on Tuesday, June 17th and the early morning hours of Wednesday, June 18th.  Along and just ahead of this boundary, a line of severe thunderstorms in the form of a squall line raced from west to east across the area.  These storms produced significant wind damage across eastern New York.  The thunderstorms weakened somewhat as they reached the border with western New England as instability started to wane.  The threat for thunderstorms ended with the passage of the cold front by the late night hours, as drier and less humid air worked into the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were reported down in Canajoharie as a result of thunderstorm winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front was draped across the region during the late afternoon and early evening hours on Friday, June 13th, while a cold front slowly approached from western New York.  ||The combination of these fronts allowed repeated rounds of slow moving thunderstorms to move across the Mohawk Valley during the late afternoon and early evening hours.  With above-normal amounts of moisture in place, rain fell very heavily across the region in a short period of time.  This led to flash flooding, with roads being washed out and a few homes being impacted by water in Montgomery County.  By the late evening hours, the fronts crossed through the region and the threat for thunderstorms ended, allowing water to recede.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain from thunderstorms caused flash flooding on the Van Wie Creek in the town of Root.  This caused Argersinger Road, Brumley Road and Anderson Road to be closed.  In addition, residents from five homes along Argersinger Road had to be evacuated due to rising flood waters. Debris from flooding washed up on State Route 5S as well.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Ahead of a slow moving cold front, a southerly flow transported plenty of moisture into the region during the day on Tuesday, June 3rd.  With a moist and unstable air mass in place, plenty of slow moving showers and thunderstorms developed ahead of the approaching boundary.  Some of these thunderstorms produced very heavy rain in a short period of time.  This led to some flash flooding, especially in urban and poor drainage areas.  In addition, a few of the thunderstorms also produced strong wind gusts, which caused damage to trees and power lines.  By the late evening, the threat for thunderstorms ended, as the frontal boundary pushed through and less humid air moved into the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were reported down at the intersection of Brookview Road and Shady Lane in East Greenbush due to thunderstorm winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm and humid air mass was in place on the evening of Tuesday, June 17th.   A strong cold front moved across the region from west to east between late in the evening on Tuesday, June 17th and the early morning hours of Wednesday, June 18th.  Along and just ahead of this boundary, a line of severe thunderstorms in the form of a squall line raced from west to east across the area.  These storms produced significant wind damage across eastern New York.  The thunderstorms weakened somewhat as they reached the border with western New England as instability started to wane.  The threat for thunderstorms ended with the passage of the cold front by the late night hours, as drier and less humid air worked into the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were down in Old Forge as a result of thunderstorm winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very moist and humid air mass was in place across the region on Wednesday, June 25th.  As a slow moving cold front approached from the west, bands of heavy rain showers and thunderstorms developed ahead of the boundary.  As these showers and thunderstorms repeatedly passed over the same locations, the heavy rainfall led to significant runoff, which caused flash flooding in some areas.  Many roads were closed due to the flooding and some homes were affected by water as well.  In addition, a few of the storms produced wind damage to trees and some damaging lightning strikes.  ||The threat for heavy rainfall and flooding ended late on the evening of June 25th, as the storm's cold front passed through the region from west to east.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding from thunderstorm heavy rain was reported in the town of Hillsdale.  A portion of Harlemville Road, off County Route 21, was washed out due to the flood waters.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent shortwave trough was moving from the eastern Great Lakes towards upstate New York during the afternoon on Thursday, May 22nd.  A complex frontal system was moving from west to east during the mid afternoon hours, with the triple point of where the occluded, cold and warm fronts meet situated over the Mohawk Valley.  There was a significant gradient along the warm front, between warm and unstable air over the Mohawk Valley and cooler, more stable air over far eastern New York that originated off the western Atlantic Ocean.||As a result, a large supercell thunderstorm developed along this boundary over the southern Adirondacks and eastern Mohawk Valley and it quickly strengthened.  It produced very large hail as large as 4 inches in diameter in the Amsterdam area.  As this storm continued to strengthen even further, it moved south to southeast towards the Helderbergs and western parts of the Capital Region, where it produced a tornado.  The tornado was on the ground for 7 miles and reached EF3 strength with maximum winds of 140 MPH, as it passed through the town of Duanesburg. The tornado dissipated once it reached western Albany County, and the more stable air in place allowed thunderstorms to weaken as they reached the Hudson Valley. Aside from one additional report of large hail in the mid-Hudson valley, no other thunderstorms reached severe levels and the threat for storms diminished by the evening with passage of the occluded boundary.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A member of the public reported baseball size hail falling on Frederick Street in Amsterdam during a thunderstorm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Ahead of a slow moving cold front, a southerly flow transported plenty of moisture into the region during the day on Tuesday, June 3rd. With a moist and unstable air mass in place, plenty of slow moving showers and thunderstorms developed ahead of the approaching boundary. Some of these thunderstorms produced very heavy rain in a short period of time. This led to some flash flooding, especially in urban and poor drainage areas. In addition, a few of the thunderstorms also produced strong wind gusts, which caused damage to trees and power lines. By the late evening, the threat for thunderstorms ended, as the frontal boundary pushed through and less humid air moved into the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A portion of Lenox Branch Road in West Stockbridge was washed out due to flash flooding from thunderstorm heavy rainfall.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent shortwave trough was moving from the eastern Great Lakes towards upstate New York during the afternoon on Thursday, May 22nd.  A complex frontal system was moving from west to east during the mid afternoon hours, with the triple point of where the occluded, cold and warm fronts meet situated over the Mohawk Valley.  There was a significant gradient along the warm front, between warm and unstable air over the Mohawk Valley and cooler, more stable air over far eastern New York that originated off the western Atlantic Ocean.||As a result, a large supercell thunderstorm developed along this boundary over the southern Adirondacks and eastern Mohawk Valley and it quickly strengthened.  It produced very large hail as large as 4 inches in diameter in the Amsterdam area.  As this storm continued to strengthen even further, it moved south to southeast towards the Helderbergs and western parts of the Capital Region, where it produced a tornado.  The tornado was on the ground for 7 miles and reached EF3 strength with maximum winds of 140 MPH, as it passed through the town of Duanesburg. The tornado dissipated once it reached western Albany County, and the more stable air in place allowed thunderstorms to weaken as they reached the Hudson Valley. Aside from one additional report of large hail in the mid-Hudson valley, no other thunderstorms reached severe levels and the threat for storms diminished by the evening with passage of the occluded boundary.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several members of the public reported hail measuring as large as 2.25 inches in diameter in Perth during a thunderstorm.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rain bands associated with Hurricane Arthur produced generally one to two inches of rainfall across portions of the county. Norfolk International Airport (ORF) reported 1.46 inches of rain. Wind gust of 38 knots was measured at Norfolk NAS (NGU). Wind gust of 40 knots was measured at Saint Helena.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A persistent cluster of heavy showers and thunderstorms moved down the coast of St. Lucie and Martin Counties and produced a localized area of very high winds within the town of Hobe Sound. Twenty mobile homes sustained mainly minor wind damage, with moderate damage to two homes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A NWS Storm Survey confirmed a zone of straight-line wind damage approximately aligned northeast to southwest, approximately one-third of a mile long and up to about 300 feet wide, affecting the Woodbridge Mobile Home park in the town of Hobe Sound. Twenty mobile homes sustained wind damage. Carports and awnings were removed from homes, and several homes had parts of their metal roofs peeled back. Two large trees sustained damage, primarily from debris impact. Damage estimates totalled $150,000.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A back door cold front moved into the region with east winds bringing in deep moisture up to about the Rio Grande Valley. Upper level flow was out of the northwest providing sufficient shear for some severe thunderstorms to develop and some isolated flash flooding. Wind gusts up to 66 mph and hail up to an inch and a half in diameter were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Las Cruces Police reported flooding in the Picacho Hills area down by the river.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several unseasonably strong cold fronts passed through eastern Oklahoma during July 2014. Along with the mild temperatures that came with the fronts, some widespread rainfall fell across the area, especially across southeastern Oklahoma where rainfall was between 100 and 300 percent of the long-term climatological normal. Far northeastern Oklahoma experienced conditions that were drastically different during the month with a lot of the region only receiving between 25 and 50 percent of average rainfall for the month. The long-term drought conditions improved over southeastern Oklahoma but remained across much of northeastern Oklahoma. Severe drought (D2) conditions persisted during the month across portions of Okfuskee, Okmulgee, Tulsa, Washington, Rogers, Nowata, and Craig Counties with extreme drought (D3) conditions continuing across portions of Creek, Pawnee, and Osage Counties. Monetary damage estimates resulting from the drought were not available.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper-level ridge during the end of July and beginning August helped fuel a moist and unstable air mass over the region. The ridge broke down on the 1st of August and was overrun by two weak midlevel impulses on August 2nd. As the second impulse passed over Northeastern Washington and Northern Idaho strong storms developed.  Meanwhile, dewpoint depressions over Northern Idaho had spread between 40 and 50 degrees Fahrenheit. The rain and hail cooled outflow winds from storms over Northeastern Washington and North Idaho put out damaging outflow winds which moved northwest to southeast and gained momentum while tracking off the Selkirk Mountain Range.  Winds ranging between 50 and 70 miles per hour blew through Priest Lake, Sandpoint, Lake Pend Oreille, and Prichard.  Meanwhile, isolated thunderstorms were developing along a decaying outflow boundary tracking west to east across the Washington, Idaho border, each producing local tree damage.  Priest Lake, Sandpoint, and communities surrounding Lake Pend Oreille were the hardest hit areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Coeur D Alene Press reported that thunderstorms brought high winds and downed trees across portions of Post Falls, Hayden, Spirit Lake, and northern Coeur D'Alene.  The Stateline Speedway and several other businesses on Pleasant View Road lost power and were forced to cancel the Idaho 200 race.  The storm and strong winds also sparked a quick grass fire causing Love's Travel Center to evacuate.  The storm was also blamed for a house fire on Cimmaron Street in Post Falls and another one at Fir and 13th Street caused by downed power lines.

Scattered thunderstorms affected much of south central Arizona during the afternoon and evening hours on August 3rd, and some of the areas impacted included Wickenburg as well as the greater Phoenix metropolitan area. The stronger thunderstorms produced locally heavy rain with rain rates approaching 2 inches per hour. Additionally, they generated gusty and damaging microburst winds; some of most significant damage occurred in the town of Tempe. Several Flash Flood and Severe Thunderstorm warnings were issued for south central Arizona as a result of the strong thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong thunderstorms developed in the Wickenburg area during the late afternoon hours on August 3rd, and they produced damaging microburst outflow winds estimated to be nearly 70 mph in strength. According to a trained weather spotter located in northwest Wickenburg, the microburst winds produced roof damage in downtown Wickenburg. A Severe Thunderstorm Warning was issued for Wickenburg at 1720MST and it continued until 1745MST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A compact, well-defined, upper level disturbance tracked along and south of Interstate 94 during the late afternoon and early evening of the 16th. It was an extremely slow moving feature, as wind speeds were very weak. Thunderstorms that were associated with it produced heavy rain, funnel clouds, and isolated strong wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A boat was sunk by the heavy rain. The rain guage read over four inches, but was blocked by leaves, so an accurate reading was impossible.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of showers and thunderstorms passed through Grant County during the early morning hours of the 24th. This rainfall may have helped to mix some of the stronger winds aloft down to the surface. Several pine trees in the Herman area were blown over by these strong wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several ten to twenty foot tall pine trees were blown over during a protracted period of heavy rain and strong gusty winds.

Over time a strong cold pool developed and drove the storms into north central Kansas by the evening. These storms caused severe wind damage to certain locations before the nocturnal inversion began preventing the winds from reaching the surface.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Power lines and trees down which are blocking emergency services from entering the town.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms continued to develop across south central Arizona during the afternoon hours on August 12th, and they persisted well into the evening. Many of the storms affected the greater Phoenix metropolitan area. Due to excessively moist atmospheric conditions, a Flash Flood Watch was in effect from noon August 12th through 5 am on Wednesday August 13th. Many of the thunderstorms produced locally heavy rain with rainfall rates in excess of 2 inches per hour at times. The heavy rain led to urban flooding, flash flooding, and eventually areal flooding which affected much of the greater Phoenix area, especially the southeast and south central portions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Scattered to numerous thunderstorms developed across the southeastern portions of the greater Phoenix metropolitan area during the afternoon hours on August 12th, and they affected communities such as Mesa and Gilbert. The stronger storms produced locally heavy rainfall with peak rain rates in excess of 2 inches per hour. The heavy rain led to significant urban flooding; at 1639MST a trained spotter 4 miles northwest of Gilbert reported very heavy rain and street flooding at the intersection of Baseline Road and Gilbert Road. The rain was so heavy that visibility was lowered to near zero miles. A Flash Flood Warning was in effect at the time of the spotter report.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed across portions of southern Gila county during the afternoon hours on August 17th, and due to favorable atmospheric conditions they were able to generate gusty and damaging microburst winds with peak gusts in excess of 60 mph. Some of the communities affected included Globe and Claypool. Gusty outflow winds were sufficient to cause roof damage near Globe. Severe Thunderstorm Warnings were issued as a result of the strong thunderstorms; fortunately no injuries were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed across portions of southern Gila county during the afternoon hours on August 17th and some of them affected the community of Claypool. The stronger storms generated gusty outflow winds in excess of 60 mph; a trained weather spotter located about 3 miles east of Claypool measured a wind gust to 70 mph. No damage was reported due to the strong winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An active monsoon pattern that characterized July 2014 continued into August, with an especially wet period during the first several days of the month. Widespread heavy rain eased from the 6th through 8th, however, as more typical isolated to scattered thunderstorms dominated the landscape from the 9th through 12th.  A monsoon burst, aided by a subtropical low pressure system aloft, brought heavy rain and local flash flooding on the 13th and 14th. Drier air worked into the northwest parts of the state with much less storm activity from the 15th into the 21st. Another good surge of monsoon moisture from the south arrived late on the 21st with widespread showers and storms on the 22nd, some with heavy rain and flash flooding. The 23rd was much drier then a gradual increase in moisture returned on the 24th and continued into the 27th. The 26th was an active day with a few reports of significant flash flooding. The remainder of the month turned much drier and warmer.  Despite the active monsoon,  New Mexico's rangeland and pastures were rated 56% very poor to poor at the beginning of the month,  with  only modest improvements during the month. Despite short-term gains,  longer-term hydrological impacts (below-normal reservoir levels) remained after multiple years of below-normal snowpack. The Middle Rio Grande Conservancy District curtailed water bank deliveries for irrigation in response to low flows along the Rio Grande during the month. The combination of short- and long-term hydrological impacts, below-normal mountain snowpack conditions in the headwater regions led to the re-introduction of an area of Moderate Drought (D1) in the Middle Rio Grande corridor from Socorro County northward to Sante Fe County.

Most of eastern Oklahoma received below normal rainfall during August 2014 with some areas not even receiving 10 percent of their normal average precipitation for the month. Severe drought (D2) conditions continued across much of northeastern Oklahoma, including Osage, Washington, Nowata, Craig, Tulsa, Rogers, Okfuskee, and Okmulgee Counties with extreme drought (D3) conditions persisting across portions of Creek and Pawnee Counties. Monetary damage estimates resulting from the drought were not available.

A low pressure system dropped down the west coast and settled south of the Four Corners to end out 2014. This circulation brought significant snowfall to the lower elevations of southeast Utah near the 4 Corners where 3 to 5 inches fell by the first day of the new year.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snowfall of 3 to 4 inches fell over far southeast Utah including the Valley of the Gods.

The combination of short- and long-term hydrological impacts, below-normal mountain snowpack conditions in the headwater regions led to the re-introduction of an area of Moderate Drought (D1) in the Middle Rio Grande corridor from Socorro County northward to Sante Fe County.

Extreme drought (D3) conditions continued across part of southeast Arizona during August, but the overall area was reduced due to monsoonal rainfall. Portions of Cochise, Greenlee, Pima and northern Graham counties improved into the severe or moderate drought categories by month's end.  Western Graham and southeast Pinal counties remained in the extreme drought category.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: By early August, extreme drought (D3) conditions were reduced to the severe (D2) category across the White Mountains of Graham and Greenlee counties and the northern Chiricahua Mountains as a result of significant late July and early August rainfall.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Portions of northern Stark County Ohio saw a series of thunderstorms with intense rain over three days. The first storm occurred primarily over the Canton/Northern Canton area with rainfall amounts around 3 inches.  Between 4 AM and 6 AM on the morning of the 18th another thunderstorm rolled through north/northeast Stark County. This line of storms brought 1 to 1.5 inches of rainfall notably over the Louisville area. Later in the evening of the 18th a storm brought 1 to 1.5 inches to north/northwest Stark County. Each event unfolded with flash floods, the later ones enhanced by already saturated ground cover and backed up rivers and tributaries of the Nimishillen River. Overall an estimated 1,000 sustained some form of water damage, mostly in basements. Dozens of businesses were inundated and dozens of people were evacuated.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 4 and 6 AM on the morning of June 18th heavy rain moved over the Summit and Stark county-line. The measured rainfall amounts for 24 hours ending at 7 am that morning were: 2.09 at Akron/Canton airport, 2.35 at Berlin Lake, 1.84 in Barberton, 3.90 in Uniontown and Mayfair Road. The great majority of the rain fell that morning. This rainfall fell on already saturated ground cover from flooding less than 36 hours earlier. The East Branch of the Nimishillen Creek could not handle the excessive runoff and it flooded a large portion of Louisville. Several businesses and homes were inundated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed across Ohio on June 11th ahead of a low pressure system located near Chicago. Instability was fairly low but enhanced winds moving through an upper level trough aloft resulted in a severe thunderstorm producing damaging winds that tracked from near Youngstown in Mahoning County to Hubbard in Trumbull County. Numerous trees were uprooted with this storm. Damage was also reported in Mill Creek Metropark where several roads were closed due to downed trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees and power lines were brought down by strong thunderstorm winds in Hubbard.  One tree fell onto a pick-up truck.

Another good surge of monsoon moisture from the south arrived late on the 21st with widespread showers and storms on the 22nd, some with heavy rain and flash flooding. The Middle Rio Grande Conservancy District curtailed water bank deliveries for irrigation in response to low flows along the Rio Grande during the month. The combination of short- and long-term hydrological impacts, below-normal mountain snowpack conditions in the headwater regions led to the re-introduction of an area of Moderate Drought (D1) in the Middle Rio Grande corridor from Socorro County northward to Sante Fe County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By the early morning hours of the 4th, an area of surface low pressure had moved into northeast South Dakota, with a warm front extending out to the east. Surface dew point values north of the front ranged in the lower 60s while south of the front they topped out around 70. At 850 millibars, the low level jet pushed juicy air up into southeast North Dakota and west central Minnesota, with drier air to the north. Finally, forty-five to fifty knot westerly winds at 500 millibars provided ample shear to the system. Thunderstorms over western and central North Dakota proceeded east and moved into Barnes County, North Dakota, during the first few hours of the 4th. These storms tracked nearly due east, finally exiting Wadena County, Minnesota, around sunrise. The strongest storms mainly stayed along and south of Interstate 94 in North Dakota and U. S. Highway 10 in Minnesota. These storms trained across the same areas as well, with some spots experiencing large hail or damaging winds two or three times during the event. In addition, heavy rainfall became a problem, resulting in some flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Streets were flooded in south Moorhead.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: September was a bit a mixed bag as far as rainfall west across South Central Texas. About half of the area had above normal precipitation and about half had less than normal. As a result none of our counties worsened during the month. Bandera, Gillespie, Kendall, Kerr, and Val Verde Counties improved to Severe Drought category (Stage D2). Medina County remain in Extreme Drought category (Stage D3) and Bexar, Blanco, Burnet, Comal, De Witt, Edwards, Llano, and Real Counties remained in Stage D2. Fire danger was moderate across the area at the end of September.  Of the counties in D2 or worse drought Bexar, Burnet, Comal, Kerr, De Witt, Medina, and Val Verde had burn bans remaining in effect. The seven day stream flow averages at the end of the month were below normal (10-24 percent) for the Middle San Antonio, Nueces, Medina, and Frio River basins. The Lower Colorado, the Upper, and the Lower San Antonio River Basins were much below normal (less than 10 percent). Area lakes and reservoirs continued well below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad had marked improvement was 33.9 feet below normal. Lake Travis was up slightly at 57.1 feet below normal. Medina Lake dropped again and was 88.3 feet below normal. The Edwards Aquifer rose a couple of feet during the month and was at 628.8 feet. This was 8.2 feet lower than at the end of September 2013 and 35 feet below average. The Edwards Aquifer Authority continued stage 4 water restrictions requiring large water users to reduce pumping by 40%. The Barton Springs Edwards Aquifer Conservation District declared stage 2 alarm drought status requiring a 20% reduction in pumping. San Marcos was in stage 4 water restrictions, Fredericksburg and New Braunfels were in stage 3, Kerrville, San Antonio Water System (SAWS), and Austin were in stage 2, and Del Rio and Seguin were in stage 1.

During the late afternoon of July 21st, a stationary boundary set up across northeast North Dakota. Temperatures north of the boundary were generally in the low to mid 80s, while to the south they were in the mid 80s to low 90s. Surface dew point readings were very high, with most locations in the low to mid 70s. A few thunderstorms fired north of the front around the Langdon, ND, area, dropping some large hail. However, the more significant action came from a thunderstorm complex that formed across west central North Dakota and moved east during the evening. This complex evolved into a bow echo with good rotational structure on the northern book end vortice. Strong straight line winds, large hail, and a few tornadoes were reported as this complex moved across eastern North Dakota into the northwest quarter of Minnesota.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The peak wind was measured at the Thief River Falls Regional Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A majority of central and northern New Mexico received below normal precipitation during April 2014.  As a result,  severe (D2) or worse drought conditions expanded areawide and worsened for parts of the far east, central and west.  An estimated 86 percent of the state was classified in severe drought or worse at the end of April,  as compared to 65 per cent at the beginning of the month.  Exceptional drought (D4) returned to far eastern New Mexico from the Clovis area north to Tucumcari and Clayton.

A large regional severe weather outbreak affected the Tennessee and lower Mississippi Valleys with a mixture of isolated supercells and multicell line segments impacting Middle Tennessee. One supercell thunderstorm moved rapidly northeast across northwest Perry, Humphreys, eastern Houston, and Montgomery Counties, bringing numerous reports of large hail, wind damage, and one EF1 tornado. Other strong to severe thunderstorms brought wind damage and flash flooding to much of the rest of Middle Tennessee.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Power lines were blown down west of Loretto.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread rain, along with multiple embedded lines of showers and low-topped thunderstorms developed across the Upstate throughout the 14th within a highly sheared, weakly unstable air mass. A couple of brief, weak tornadoes occurred across the foothills, while some isolated wind damage was also reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: NWS Storm Survey team found the short path of a weak tornado on the grounds of a wilderness school off of Highway 76 near Westminster. Damage was confined to a couple of dozen uprooted trees in this rural area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front was dropping south through New Mexico with an upper level trough moving across the Rockies. These two features combined to create a moderately unstable atmosphere with one stronger thunderstorm producing hail up to the size of dimes and moderate to heavy rain.

An upper level trough was over New Mexico with lift enhanced along and just ahead of this trough.  A cold front was in the Texas panhandle moving southward.  The lift from the trough combined with the lift from the approaching front.  Abundant moisture was also available across the area.  Winds were changing direction and increasing in speed with height.  These conditions resulted in thunderstorms developing with large hail.

However, some storms in the Pine Belt became strong to severe during the latter evening hours as a low pressure system moved through that region. This produced some wind damage and a tornado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level trough moved quickly into the Central and Southern Plains providing the necessary lift for scattered strong to severe thunderstorms across Northwest Texas and Western Oklahoma during the evening hours of Sunday, Oct. 12th. At the surface, a warm front was rapidly moving northward across East Texas and North Louisiana with low level moisture returning quickly in the wake of the northward moving warm front. A cold front in association with the upper level trough was rapidly moving eastward through Western Oklahoma and Texas. Overnight across Southeast Oklahoma, Southwest Arkansas, Northeast Texas and Northwest Louisiana, moderate instability was in place with increasing low and mid-level shear as the upper trough approached from the west. Storms eventually erupted ahead of the cold front across Central Oklahoma and Northern Texas, maturing into a squall line as it approached the region during the predawn hours of Monday, Oct. 13th. As the squall line traversed through the region, widespread wind damage was reported associated with straight line winds. Several short track, intense tornadoes developed along the leading edge of the squall line as well across portions of Northeast Texas, Southwest Arkansas and Northern Louisiana. The storms finally exited the region during the afternoon hours of Oct. 13th. Post-event Storm Surveys determined that 6 tornadoes occurred with this severe weather outbreak, one of which produced 1 fatality and 4 injuries in Little River County, Arkansas. Another tornado produced widespread damage across Ouachita Parish in Monroe, Louisiana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were downed near Bawcomville, Louisiana.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Colder air in the wake of a low pressure system moving through the Upper Great Lakes brought moderate lake effect snow accumulation to portions of west and north central Upper Michigan from the evening of the 30th through the 31st.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The observer near Three Lakes measured eight inches of total lake effect snow accumulation.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level trough moved quickly into the Central and Southern Plains providing the necessary lift for scattered strong to severe thunderstorms across Northwest Texas and Western Oklahoma during the evening hours of Sunday, Oct. 12th.  At the surface, a warm front  was rapidly moving northward across East Texas and North Louisiana with low level moisture returning quickly in the wake of the northward moving warm front.  A cold front in association with the upper level trough was rapidly moving eastward through Western Oklahoma and Texas.  Overnight across Southeast Oklahoma, Southwest Arkansas, Northeast Texas and Northwest Louisiana, moderate instability was in place with increasing low and mid-level shear as the upper trough approached from the west. Storms eventually erupted ahead of the cold front across Central Oklahoma and Northern Texas, maturing into a squall line as it approached the region during the predawn hours of Monday, Oct. 13th.  As the squall line traversed through the region, widespread wind damage was reported associated with straight line winds.  Several short track, intense tornadoes developed along the leading edge of the squall line as well across portions of Northeast Texas, Southwest Arkansas and Northern Louisiana.  The storms finally exited the region during the afternoon hours of Oct. 13th.  Post-event Storm Surveys determined that 6 tornadoes occurred with this severe weather outbreak, one of which produced 1 fatality and 4 injuries in Little River County, Arkansas.  Another tornado produced widespread damage across Ouachita Parish in Monroe, Louisiana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were downed along with a barn that was blow down and powerlines north of Leesburg between Leesburg and Lake Bob Sandlin.  Several roads were blocked by fallen trees as well.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Repeated thunderstorms in late August led to flooding along several rivers in eastern Nebraska and western Iowa. Some of the rivers remained in flood into early September.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy Rainfall in northwest Iowa in late August led to minor flooding along the Boyer River. The river rose above flood stage in the early morning on the first, and created and fell below flood stage later that morning.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Repeated thunderstorms in late August led to flooding along several rivers in eastern Nebraska and western Iowa. Some of the rivers remained in flood into early September.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rainfall at the end of August allowed the West Nishnabotna River to rise above flood stage on the early morning on the 1st, crest during the early afternoon, and fall below flood stage during the early evening. The flooding was minor and confined to low-lying areas along the river.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A generally wet period with repeated thunderstorms from August into early September led to a number of area rivers having above normal river levels. A slow moving complex of thunderstorms near the 10th of September set rivers in southeast Nebraska and southwest Iowa above flood stage. This included the Missouri and the Big Blue Rivers in Nebraska, and the East Nishnabotna, main stem of the Nishnabotna, and Nodaway Rivers in southwest Iowa.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A slow moving thunderstorm complex lead to heavy rainfall on the 9th causing the East Nishnabotna River to rise above flood stage around the Red Oak area. The river rose above flood stage during the early morning on the 10th, crested during mid afternoon and fell below flood stage during the evening. The flooding was minor and confined to low-lying areas.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous upper level trough moved out of the Southern Plains and into the Lower Mississippi Valley during the late afternoon and evening hours of October 2nd. This upper level trough took on a negative tilt as it moved towards the Four State Region, with vigorous lift resulting in the development of severe thunderstorms in a moderately unstable environment. Strong unidirectional deep layer shear resulted in the convection eventually taking on the shape of a squall line which raced through the region producing widespread wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were downed across Hwy. 237 in Texarkana, Arkansas.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: With a surface trough northwest of the Aloha State, surface winds became light and from the southeast.  This resulted in afternoon and evening cloud buildups over portions of Oahu and the Big Island of Hawaii.  The heavy rain that occurred caused ponding on roadways, and small stream and drainage ditch flooding.  There were no reports of significant property damage or injuries.

Heavy downpours occurred over portions of North and South Kohala on the lee side of the Big Island of Hawaii.  The rain produced small stream and drainage ditch flooding, and ponding on roadways.  No serious injuries or property damage were reported.

A fire charred 60 acres of brush above a Kaanapali Coffee farm in west Maui.  The blaze affected electric poles and downed power lines but did not damage any structures.  No serious injuries were reported.  The cost of damages was not available.  The cause of the fire was unknown.
A swell from the southern hemisphere generated surf of 6 to 10 feet along the south-facing shores of all the islands.  There were no reports of significant property damage or injuries.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Despite fairly dry conditions, a couple of rainfall events led to some drought improvement, as D2 (severe) to D3 (extreme) drought were replaced by only D2 drought by the end of the month.

Part of western Kentucky experienced its heaviest snowfall for so early in the season. The heaviest snowfall amounts were in counties along the Ohio River, which received anywhere from three to five inches. To the southeast of the Ohio River counties, anywhere from one to three inches fell along a corridor from Fulton and Mayfield to Princeton and Madisonville. Less than an inch was reported along the Tennessee border from Murray to Hopkinsville. The National Weather Service office at Paducah measured 2.8 inches, which was the heaviest snowfall for so early in the season. A weak low pressure system developed over the northern Gulf of Mexico, then moved northeast into Alabama. This system threw moisture northward into unseasonably cold air over the Lower Ohio Valley, resulting in widespread snow. Specific snowfall amounts included 5 inches at Morganfield (Union County), 5 inches about five miles south of Owensboro (Daviess County), 4 inches at Kevil (Ballard County), 3 inches at Paducah (McCracken County), 3 inches at Marion (Crittenden County), 3 inches at Hanson (Hopkins County), 2.5 inches at Eddyville (Lyon County), 2 inches at Dublin (Graves County), and one inch at Hickman (Fulton County). The snow fell at temperatures right near freezing on relatively warm pavement. The highest accumulations were on grassy areas. Roads were slush-covered and slippery during the period of heaviest snow.

An upper air disturbance combined with a low pressure system that rode along an offshore cold front to bring the first measurable snow of the season for most of New Jersey (except the southeast quarter) during the evening and overnight of the 13th. While many accumulations were less than an inch, one to four inches of snow fell over the higher terrain of northwest New Jersey.  Since the ground was warm, roadway accumulations were limited to lesser traveled roads and the snow started to melt once it stopped falling. ||Precipitation started as rain during the late afternoon in northwest New Jersey and during the early evening elsewhere in New Jersey on the 13th. Precipitation changed to snow during the early evening of the 13th in northwest New Jersey and the middle of the evening on the 13th in central and southwest New Jersey. The snow ended during the early morning of the 14th and changed to snow just before ending in the southeast part of the state early on the 14th. ||Representative snowfall included 4.0 inches in Highland Lakes (Sussex County), 3.3 inches in Jefferson Township (Morris County), 3.0 inches in Randolph Township (Morris County), 2.8 inches in Hardyston Township (Sussex County), 2.5 inches in Stockton (Sussex County), 2.0 inches in Bethlehem Township (Hunterdon County) and Liberty Township (Warren County), 1.8 inches in Kingwood Township (Hunterdon County), 1.6 inches in Marcella (Morris County) and Peapack (Somerset County) and 1.1 inches in Stewartsville (Warren County).||The snow was caused by a low pressure system that formed on a cold front over the Carolinas on the 12th. The same cold front moved through New Jersey that day and stalled offshore.   This low pressure system initially moved slowly and only reached the North Carolina coastal waters mid day on the 13th. From there it progressed northeast faster and passed east of New Jersey early on the 14th. An upper level jet streak also passed across the region overnight on the 13th and both combined to bring the snow into New Jersey.

October saw below normal precipitation for much of the Texas Panhandle, though several episodes of rainfall did keep moisture in the Panhandle throughout the month. Most areas measured at least half an inch during the month, with scattered areas measuring as much as 4 to 5 inches.  Extreme (D3) Drought remained along a line from east of Dalhart to near Clarendon and in the extreme northeastern Panhandle.  The southwestern Texas Panhandle remained a mix of Abnormally Dry (D0) to Moderate (D1) Drought conditions following rain from September and October, and areas surrounding Perryton improved to Moderate (D1) Drought conditions during October.  Otherwise, the remainder of the Panhandles were rated at Severe (D2) Drought conditions.  Amarillo recorded 1.08 inches of precipitation for the month (0.58 inches below normal), Dalhart recorded 1.01 inches of precipitation (0.46 inches below normal), and Borger recorded 0.85 inches of precipitation (0.87 inches below normal).||Soil moisture was rated mostly short to adequate during the month.  Crops fared well during the month, and some development was even limited by too much rain and cloudiness.  Rangeland and pasture continued to improve in some areas, but cattle herd sizes remained limited due to prolonged drought.  Upper soil zones were mostly in the 10 to 30 percent full range, with locations in the western Panhandle generally drier.  Deeper soil moisture was still below normal in much of the Texas Panhandle, but values were estimated to be greater than 150 percent of normal where rainfall had been most frequent over the previous few months.  The Palmer Drought Severity Index indicated a rating of Moderate Drought to Near Normal conditions for the Texas Panhandle.  Countywide burn bans were supported in several counties.||Stream flows across the Texas Panhandle ranged from near normal to below normal during October.  The reservoirs of Lake Meredith and Palo Duro were near 5 percent and 2 percent capacity respectively, and Greenbelt Lake was below 13 percent capacity.  Water watches for several public water systems persisted through October while voluntary to mandatory mild water restrictions were continued.||Economic losses due to the drought through October were predominantly the result of supplemental watering in the driest areas and supplemental feed for cattle on drought-thinned rangeland and pastures.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extreme Drought (D3) as depicted on the U.S. Drought Monitor.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Grays River near Rosburg reached the flood stage of 12 feet at 715 AM PST on December 20th. The river crested at 13.6 feet at 12:15 AM PST on December 21 before falling below flood stage at 8:15 AM PST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As the unseasonably deep upper level storm system shifted east across northern New Mexico on the 27th, strong winds and areas of blowing dust redeveloped over much of the area.  West to northwest winds were the strongest along and east of the central mountain chain where numerous locations reported peak wind gusts of around 60 to 65 mph.  No significant damage was reported on this second day either. Areas of blowing dust occurred early in the day across far eastern New Mexico before pushing east into Texas.  Showers and colder air across northern and western New Mexico produced gusty winds in those areas again however speeds were lighter than on the 26th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Angel Fire AWOS hit 46 mph sustained with a peak gust to 58 mph during the early morning hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A swell from a strong low far northwest of the islands generated surf of 10 to 20 feet along the north- and west-facing shores of Niihau and Kauai; the north-facing shores of Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; and 8 to 14 feet along the west-facing shores of Oahu and Molokai.  Lifeguards helped a 17-year-old male who was seriously injured when he was caught in the shore-break at Waimea Bay on Oahu's North Shore.  Ocean safety personnel also performed 1120 preventive actions, just on North Shore beaches.  No serious property damage was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The California drought continued in full force during the month of November, 2014. Exceptional drought was detected by the U.S. Drought Monitor for almost the entire Central California region. This extent of exceptional drought is extremely unusual for California. The 2013-2014 water year (July 1 - June 30) concluded with Fresno setting its second driest on record (4.81 inches) and Bakersfield setting its third driest (2.41 inches). ||There continues to be significant media coverage on the on-going drought conditions. These reports include discussion of significant re-allocation of water resources from the east to west side of the San Joaquin Valley, farmers forgoing planting of some crops, a decrease in the snow-related tourism activity in the Southern Sierra Nevada, reduction in air quality due to persistent stagnant air, loss or reduction of ground water, wells drying up in several communities leaving them with no water, and an unprecedented increase in fire danger across the Southern Sierra Nevada and Tehachapi Mountains. For the first time on record, red flag warnings were issued in January for not only the Southern Sierra Nevada and the Tehachapi Mountains but also the south end of the San Joaquin Valley.

A wedge of cold air was in place across the Potomac Highlands and Northern Maryland while warm air moved into the region from the Tennessee Valley. This led to overrunning and showers across the area. Freezing rain occurred for areas with surface temperatures below freezing.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulation of a trace or more was measured at surrounding locations.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A upper level trough stretched from Southern Canada to the Gulf Coast and an abundant amount of moisture was present across the Mid-Atlantic. A surface low was moving across the region in the overnight hours and showers and thunderstorms formed along the attendant cold front and surface trough.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado was estimated to have touched down at approximately 3:31 AM EDT. Peak winds were estimated to have been 65 mph. A large tree was uprooted and fell across Sally Mill Road near the intersection of Light Horse Court. Additional trees and large branches were found uprooted and collapsed in different directions along with branches snapped or twisted at various points on a large residential property along Light Horse Court. The tornado quickly lifted around 3:35 AM EDT.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The Banner Fire started around 0930 PST on July 3 in the Banner, California area, near Route 78 in San Diego County. It quickly spread westward and expanded to 150 acres, threatening the town of Julian. Portions of Route 78 were closed, and mandatory evacuation was ordered for 200 homes; however, the evacuation order was lifted later that evening, as the containment increased. Two homes were destroyed. On July 4, four injuries were reported. On July 6, at 0815 PST, the Banner Fire was 100% contained. However, the road closures still remained in effect through the day, as the firefighting crews continued to monitor the burn areas for potential flare-ups. The cause of the fire is still under investigation.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm and humid air mass combined with an approaching cold front to produce over 6 inches of rain in 2 to 4 hours causing tremendous flash flooding in eastern Cumberland County. Roads were washed out or flooded by several feet of water. Cars were submerged and evacuations ordered. In Portland the flash flooding forced the evacuation of eight properties in the city including 200 people who were staying at the La Quinta Inn on Park Avenue. In Portland over 5 inches of rain fell in 4 hours with 1.42 inches falling in 27 minutes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain produced flash flooding washing out numerous roads in the Freeport area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front sweeping across the lower Great Lakes was preceded and accompanied by severe thunderstorms. The thunderstorm winds produced widespread damage throughout the region. Trees and power lines were downed. The highest recorded gust was 66 mph at Fort Drum. Some specific reports of damage included:  trees down on Route 5 in Portland, Rockspring Road in Ashord, Old Chautauqua Road in Gerry, Allen Street in South Dayton, Boston-Colden Road in Colden, Route 20 in Pavilion, and Locust Street in Honeoye. Some of the trees were measured to 30 inches in diameter. The falling trees and limbs damaged several homes and automobiles in Marion, Scriba, West Rush and Martinsburg. In Farmington, a stretch of ten power poles was blown over by the strong winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Law enforcement reported trees and wires down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The California drought continued in full force during the month of August, 2014. Exceptional drought was detected by the U.S. Drought Monitor for almost the entire Central California region. This extent of exceptional drought is extremely unusual for California. The 2013-2014 water year (July 1 - June 30) concluded with Fresno setting its second driest on record (4.81 inches) and Bakersfield setting its third driest (2.41 inches). ||There continues to be significant media coverage on the on-going drought conditions. These reports include discussion of significant re-allocation of water resources from the east to west side of the San Joaquin Valley, farmers forgoing planting of some crops, a decrease in the snow-related tourism activity in the Southern Sierra Nevada, reduction in air quality due to persistent stagnant air, loss or reduction of ground water, and an unprecedented increase in fire danger across the Southern Sierra Nevada and Tehachapi Mountains. For the first time on record, red flag warnings were issued in January for not only the Southern Sierra Nevada and the Tehachapi Mountains but also the south end of the San Joaquin Valley.

Several unseasonably strong cold fronts passed through eastern Oklahoma during July 2014. Along with the mild temperatures that came with the fronts, some widespread rainfall fell across the area, especially across southeastern Oklahoma where rainfall was between 100 and 300 percent of the long-term climatological normal. Far northeastern Oklahoma experienced conditions that were drastically different during the month with a lot of the region only receiving between 25 and 50 percent of average rainfall for the month. The long-term drought conditions improved over southeastern Oklahoma but remained across much of northeastern Oklahoma. Severe drought (D2) conditions persisted during the month across portions of Okfuskee, Okmulgee, Tulsa, Washington, Rogers, Nowata, and Craig Counties with extreme drought (D3) conditions continuing across portions of Creek, Pawnee, and Osage Counties. Monetary damage estimates resulting from the drought were not available.
While several rainfall events occurred throughout the month, drought conditions remained mostly unchanged across Oklahoma.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Despite, several rainfall events, D2 (severe) drought persisted across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A ridge of high pressure over the region for the last few weeks was nudged east by a potent upper-level trough coming off the Eastern Pacific. The trough took on a strong negative tilt and passed through during peak heating. An east to west line of strong thunderstorms developed over Northern Oregon and tracked northward through Eastern Washington and Northern Idaho during the late afternoon and early evening. Additional storms continued to develop along the gust front which continued to pickup momentum as it passed into the region into an inverted V environment. Winds between 50 and 60 mph resulted in downed trees and power outages.  The strongest winds were observed between Latah and southern Bonner County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down on a power line in Sandpoint, ID.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Less than half an inch of rain was reported by a CoCoRaHS observer W of Rio Grande City during all of June, with all of it falling on one day.  Overall dry conditions and little rain led to the development of Severe (D2) drought conditions developing across the Upper Valley by the beginning of July.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A general lack of rainfall and hot conditions allowed for Severe (D2) drought conditions to return to the eastern half of Starr County by the beginning of July. The remainder of the county continued to experience Moderate (D1) drought conditions.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: While some welcome rain did fall over the area during the first half of July, it would not be enough to prevent the spread of intensifying drought conditions. By the end of the first full week of July, the area of Severe (D2) drought conditions had grown larger, as drier conditions spread further west across the Upper Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nearly all of Starr County was covered in Severe (D2) drought conditions by the end of the first full week of July.  Only a tiny sliver of Moderate (D1) drought conditions remained along the far northern county border.   Drought conditions would hold steady through the remainder of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: August was another mainly dry month for South Central Texas. Most of the region had below normal precipitation and much of that area had 50 percent or less than normal. As a result Bandera, Kendall, Kerr, and Medina Counties worsened to extreme drought category (Stage D3) and Bastrop, Bexar, Burnet, Caldwell, Comal, De Witt, Guadalupe, Hays, Real, and Travis moved into severe category (Stage D2). Gillespie and Val Verde remained in Stage D3 while Blanco, Edwards, and Llano continued in Stage D2. Fire danger was moderate to high across the area at the end of August.  Of the counties in D2 or worse drought Blanco, Kendall, Kerr, Llano, Medina, and Val Verde had burn bans remaining in effect and Bexar, Burnet, Caldwell, Comal, De Witt, Guadalupe, Hays, and Travis Counties instituted them during the month. The seven day stream flow averages at the end of the month were below normal (10-24 percent) for the Upper San Antonio, Upper Colorado, Medina, and Frio River basins. The Lower Colorado and Guadalupe River Basins were much below normal (less than 10 percent). Area lakes and reservoirs continued well below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was 41.6 feet below normal. Lake Travis dropped more than three feet to 57.4 feet below normal. Medina Lake dropped again and was 87.1 feet below normal. The Edwards Aquifer dropped during the month and was at 626.4 feet which was 2.5 feet lower than the beginning of the month and 5.1 feet below the level at the end of August 2013. The Edwards Aquifer Authority continued stage 4 water restrictions requiring large water users to reduce pumping by 40%. The Barton Springs Edwards Aquifer Conservation District declared stage 2 alarm drought status requiring a 20% reduction in pumping. San Marcos was in stage 4 water restrictions, Fredericksburg and New Braunfels were in stage 3, Kerrville, San Antonio Water System (SAWS), and Austin were in stage 2, and Del Rio and Seguin were in stage 1.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: August was another mainly dry month for South Central Texas. Most of the region had below normal precipitation and much of that area had 50 percent or less than normal. As a result Bandera, Kendall, Kerr, and Medina Counties worsened to extreme drought category (Stage D3) and Bastrop, Bexar, Burnet, Caldwell, Comal, De Witt, Guadalupe, Hays, Real, and Travis moved into severe category (Stage D2). Gillespie and Val Verde remained in Stage D3 while Blanco, Edwards, and Llano continued in Stage D2. Fire danger was moderate to high across the area at the end of August.  Of the counties in D2 or worse drought Blanco, Kendall, Kerr, Llano, Medina, and Val Verde had burn bans remaining in effect and Bexar, Burnet, Caldwell, Comal, De Witt, Guadalupe, Hays, and Travis Counties instituted them during the month. The seven day stream flow averages at the end of the month were below normal (10-24 percent) for the Upper San Antonio, Upper Colorado, Medina, and Frio River basins. The Lower Colorado and Guadalupe River Basins were much below normal (less than 10 percent). Area lakes and reservoirs continued well below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was 41.6 feet below normal. Lake Travis dropped more than three feet to 57.4 feet below normal. Medina Lake dropped again and was 87.1 feet below normal. The Edwards Aquifer dropped during the month and was at 626.4 feet which was 2.5 feet lower than the beginning of the month and 5.1 feet below the level at the end of August 2013. The Edwards Aquifer Authority continued stage 4 water restrictions requiring large water users to reduce pumping by 40%. The Barton Springs Edwards Aquifer Conservation District declared stage 2 alarm drought status requiring a 20% reduction in pumping. San Marcos was in stage 4 water restrictions, Fredericksburg and New Braunfels were in stage 3, Kerrville, San Antonio Water System (SAWS), and Austin were in stage 2, and Del Rio and Seguin were in stage 1.
