A low pressure system approaching from the west moved inland over the Pacific Northwest, putting Central Montana underneath a strong southwest flow aloft. The increased pressure gradient over the region resulted in strong winds, with Northern Rocky Mountain Front locations seeing high wind criteria.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High wind gusts, measuring 56KT (65MPH), were reported 13 mi WSW of Saint Mary, MT at the Logan Pass Visitor's Center.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous low pressure system moved southeast from Alberta into MT, bringing widespread precipitation to Central/North Central MT. Snow levels fell as cool air moved in behind the system and significant accumulating snowfall was seen, mostly at higher elevations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow, measuring 8.0 inches in 12 hours, was reported at the Pike Creek SNOTEL; elevation 5928 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Part of western Kentucky experienced its heaviest snowfall for so early in the season. The heaviest snowfall amounts were in counties along the Ohio River, which received anywhere from three to five inches. To the southeast of the Ohio River counties, anywhere from one to three inches fell along a corridor from Fulton and Mayfield to Princeton and Madisonville. Less than an inch was reported along the Tennessee border from Murray to Hopkinsville. The National Weather Service office at Paducah measured 2.8 inches, which was the heaviest snowfall for so early in the season. A weak low pressure system developed over the northern Gulf of Mexico, then moved northeast into Alabama. This system threw moisture northward into unseasonably cold air over the Lower Ohio Valley, resulting in widespread snow. Specific snowfall amounts included 5 inches at Morganfield (Union County), 5 inches about five miles south of Owensboro (Daviess County), 4 inches at Kevil (Ballard County), 3 inches at Paducah (McCracken County), 3 inches at Marion (Crittenden County), 3 inches at Hanson (Hopkins County), 2.5 inches at Eddyville (Lyon County), 2 inches at Dublin (Graves County), and one inch at Hickman (Fulton County). The snow fell at temperatures right near freezing on relatively warm pavement. The highest accumulations were on grassy areas. Roads were slush-covered and slippery during the period of heaviest snow.

An upper air disturbance combined with a low pressure system that rode along an offshore cold front to bring the first measurable snow of the season for most of Eastern Pennsylvania (except right along the Delaware River) during the evening and overnight of the 13th. While many accumulations were less than an inch, one to four inches of snow fell over the higher terrain. Since the ground was warm, roadway accumulations were limited to lesser traveled roads and the snow started to melt once it stopped falling. Less traveled roadways in Berks County were described as slippery.||Over the Poconos, precipitation fell as snow from the late afternoon on the 13th until shortly after midnight EST on the 14th. Elsewhere, precipitation started as rain during the middle afternoon and changed over to snow during the late afternoon in Berks County, around 6 p.m. EST in the Lehigh Valley and the northwest suburbs of Philadelphia and during the middle of the evening in and near the local Philadelphia area. The snow ended during the middle to late evening on the 13th. ||Representative snowfall included 3.7 inches in Williams Township (Northampton County), 3.3 inches in Salisbury Township (Lehigh County), 2.5 inches in Saylorsburg (Monroe County) and Fleetwood and Huffs Church (Berks County), 2.1 inches at West Caln Township (Chester County), 2.0 inches in Pocono Summit (Monroe County), 1.8 inches in Elverson (Chester County), 1.6 inches in Mohnton (Berks County), 1.5 inches in Souderton (Montgomery County) and 0.5 inches at the Lehigh Valley International Airport. ||The snow was caused by a low pressure system that formed on a cold front over the Carolinas on the 12th. The same cold front moved through Pennsylvania that day and stalled offshore. This low pressure system initially moved slowly and only reached the North Carolina coastal waters mid day on the 13th. From there it progressed northeast faster and passed east of New Jersey early on the 14th. An upper level jet streak also passed across the region overnight on the 13th and both combined to bring the snow into Eastern Pennsylvania.

A majority of central and northern New Mexico received below normal precipitation during April 2014.  As a result,  severe (D2) or worse drought conditions expanded areawide and worsened for parts of the far east, central and west.  An estimated 86 percent of the state was classified in severe drought or worse at the end of April,  as compared to 65 per cent at the beginning of the month.  Exceptional drought (D4) returned to far eastern New Mexico from the Clovis area north to Tucumcari and Clayton.

A strong cold front sweeping across the lower Great Lakes was preceded and accompanied by severe thunderstorms. The thunderstorm winds produced widespread damage throughout the region. Trees and power lines were downed. The highest recorded gust was 66 mph at Fort Drum. Some specific reports of damage included:  trees down on Route 5 in Portland, Rockspring Road in Ashord, Old Chautauqua Road in Gerry, Allen Street in South Dayton, Boston-Colden Road in Colden, Route 20 in Pavilion, and Locust Street in Honeoye. Some of the trees were measured to 30 inches in diameter. The falling trees and limbs damaged several homes and automobiles in Marion, Scriba, West Rush and Martinsburg. In Farmington, a stretch of ten power poles was blown over by the strong winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Local television showed a tree down on a house.

Widespread and at times moderate to heavy rainfall affected North-Central Montana as a broad, potent low pressure system with plenty of moisture and energy moved east over the Northern Rockies. Periods of rain and isolated thunderstorms also affected the region. Total rainfall amounts generally ranged from 1 to 2 inches over North-Central Montana with only 0.25 to 0.75 inches across Southwest Montana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain, measuring over 1.00 inches in 1 hour, was reported.

Widespread severe thunderstorms downed numerous trees across a large swath of eastern Kentucky during the afternoon and evening hours of September 2nd. Thunderstorms first began forming along an old outflow boundary just before 4 pm on this date. With the amount of moisture and instability in place, it wasn't long before a number of these storms began producing damaging wind gusts. The last of the storms weakened below severe limits just before 7 pm.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down and across KY 979.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed across the south central deserts during the afternoon hours on July 13th, and they primarily affected the greater Phoenix metropolitan area. Several of the storms produced microburst winds in excess of 60 mph, damaging trees, signs and buildings across the greater Phoenix area. The storms prompted the issuance of many Severe Thunderstorm Warnings. In addition, the storms produced locally heavy rains with rainfall rates in excess of 2 inches per hour. The rain led to widespread urban flooding, and prompted the issuance of several Urban and Small Stream Flood Advisories as well as Flash Flood Warnings.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms affected much of the greater Phoenix area, including southeast valley communities such as Tempe and Chandler, during the late afternoon hours on July 13th. The stronger thunderstorms generated gusty and damaging microburst winds, estimated to be in excess of 60 mph. At about 1710MST, a report was received from an amateur radio operator in south Tempe who reported that multiple trees were blown down near the intersection of Warner and McClintock roads. At nearly the same time, a trained weather spotter about 1 mile north of the Chandler Fashion Center mall reported a number of trees blown down with diameters of up to 13 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed across the south central deserts during the afternoon hours on July 13th, and they primarily affected the greater Phoenix metropolitan area. Several of the storms produced microburst winds in excess of 60 mph, damaging trees, signs and buildings across the greater Phoenix area. The storms prompted the issuance of many Severe Thunderstorm Warnings. In addition, the storms produced locally heavy rains with rainfall rates in excess of 2 inches per hour. The rain led to widespread urban flooding, and prompted the issuance of several Urban and Small Stream Flood Advisories as well as Flash Flood Warnings.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms affected much of the greater Phoenix area, including southeastern valley communities such as Gilbert, during the late afternoon hours on July 13th. The stronger storms produced damaging microburst winds in excess of 50 mph. A trained weather spotter 1 mile southeast of Gilbert reported that gusty outflow winds broke off a large branch which fell onto a car, damaging the vehicle. This occurred near the intersection of Loop 202 and Higley Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front moved into North Mississippi during the afternoon and evening hours of July 2nd, 2014. Showers and thunderstorms developed ahead of the front. Some storms became severe producing large hail and damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Straight line winds blew trees and power lines down in Becker.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed across the northern portion of Maricopa county, to the north of the greater Phoenix area, during the evening hours on August 25th. One of the areas affected the most by the storms was the community of Wickenburg. The stronger storms generated damaging outflow winds and locally heavy rainfall with peak rain rates well in excess of one inch per hour. The heavy rain led to flash flooding in Wickenburg; numerous homes were flooded at the Desert Cypress Mobile Home and RV park 2 miles east of town. Despite the flooding, there was no Flash Flood Warning issued, rather an Urban and Small Stream Flood Advisory was issued instead.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed across the far northern portion of the greater Phoenix area during the evening hours on August 25th, and some of the stronger storms affected the community of Wickenburg. The storms produced gusty and damaging outflow winds, with peak gusts estimated to be at least 60 mph. A trained weather spotter 1 mile northeast of Wickenburg reported that strong outflow winds snapped off a large tree branch with a diameter of 18 inches. The branch fell, causing damage to both a roof and an automobile next to the house. The home was located at the intersection of Tegner Street and Genung Avenue.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed across the northern portion of Maricopa county, to the north of the greater Phoenix area, during the evening hours on August 25th. The heavy rain led to flash flooding in Wickenburg; numerous homes were flooded at the Desert Cypress Mobile Home and RV park 2 miles east of town. Despite the flooding, there was no Flash Flood Warning issued, rather an Urban and Small Stream Flood Advisory was issued instead.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed across the Wickenburg area during the evening hours on August 25th, and some of them produced locally heavy rainfall with peak rain rates in excess of one inch per hour. According to public report, at 1914MST, 0.91 inches of rain was measured within one hour in central Wickenburg. The heavy rain led to street flooding. An Urban and Small Stream Flood Advisory had already been issued for northwest Maricopa county, including the town of Wickenburg.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: August was another mainly dry month for South Central Texas. Most of the region had below normal precipitation and much of that area had 50 percent or less than normal. As a result Bandera, Kendall, Kerr, and Medina Counties worsened to extreme drought category (Stage D3) and Bastrop, Bexar, Burnet, Caldwell, Comal, De Witt, Guadalupe, Hays, Real, and Travis moved into severe category (Stage D2). Gillespie and Val Verde remained in Stage D3 while Blanco, Edwards, and Llano continued in Stage D2. Fire danger was moderate to high across the area at the end of August.  Of the counties in D2 or worse drought Blanco, Kendall, Kerr, Llano, Medina, and Val Verde had burn bans remaining in effect and Bexar, Burnet, Caldwell, Comal, De Witt, Guadalupe, Hays, and Travis Counties instituted them during the month. The seven day stream flow averages at the end of the month were below normal (10-24 percent) for the Upper San Antonio, Upper Colorado, Medina, and Frio River basins. The Lower Colorado and Guadalupe River Basins were much below normal (less than 10 percent). Area lakes and reservoirs continued well below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was 41.6 feet below normal. Lake Travis dropped more than three feet to 57.4 feet below normal. Medina Lake dropped again and was 87.1 feet below normal. The Edwards Aquifer dropped during the month and was at 626.4 feet which was 2.5 feet lower than the beginning of the month and 5.1 feet below the level at the end of August 2013. The Edwards Aquifer Authority continued stage 4 water restrictions requiring large water users to reduce pumping by 40%. The Barton Springs Edwards Aquifer Conservation District declared stage 2 alarm drought status requiring a 20% reduction in pumping. San Marcos was in stage 4 water restrictions, Fredericksburg and New Braunfels were in stage 3, Kerrville, San Antonio Water System (SAWS), and Austin were in stage 2, and Del Rio and Seguin were in stage 1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The California drought continued in full force during the month of August, 2014. Exceptional drought was detected by the U.S. Drought Monitor for almost the entire Central California region. This extent of exceptional drought is extremely unusual for California. The 2013-2014 water year (July 1 - June 30) concluded with Fresno setting its second driest on record (4.81 inches) and Bakersfield setting its third driest (2.41 inches). ||There continues to be significant media coverage on the on-going drought conditions. These reports include discussion of significant re-allocation of water resources from the east to west side of the San Joaquin Valley, farmers forgoing planting of some crops, a decrease in the snow-related tourism activity in the Southern Sierra Nevada, reduction in air quality due to persistent stagnant air, loss or reduction of ground water, and an unprecedented increase in fire danger across the Southern Sierra Nevada and Tehachapi Mountains. For the first time on record, red flag warnings were issued in January for not only the Southern Sierra Nevada and the Tehachapi Mountains but also the south end of the San Joaquin Valley.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front sweeping across the lower Great Lakes was preceded and accompanied by severe thunderstorms. The thunderstorm winds produced widespread damage throughout the region. Trees and power lines were downed. The highest recorded gust was 66 mph at Fort Drum. Some specific reports of damage included:  trees down on Route 5 in Portland, Rockspring Road in Ashord, Old Chautauqua Road in Gerry, Allen Street in South Dayton, Boston-Colden Road in Colden, Route 20 in Pavilion, and Locust Street in Honeoye. Some of the trees were measured to 30 inches in diameter. The falling trees and limbs damaged several homes and automobiles in Marion, Scriba, West Rush and Martinsburg. In Farmington, a stretch of ten power poles was blown over by the strong winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Law enforcement reported trees and wires down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By the early morning hours of the 4th, an area of surface low pressure had moved into northeast South Dakota, with a warm front extending out to the east. Surface dew point values north of the front ranged in the lower 60s while south of the front they topped out around 70. At 850 millibars, the low level jet pushed juicy air up into southeast North Dakota and west central Minnesota, with drier air to the north. Finally, forty-five to fifty knot westerly winds at 500 millibars provided ample shear to the system. Thunderstorms over western and central North Dakota proceeded east and moved into Barnes County, North Dakota, during the first few hours of the 4th. These storms tracked nearly due east, finally exiting Wadena County, Minnesota, around sunrise. The strongest storms mainly stayed along and south of Interstate 94 in North Dakota and U. S. Highway 10 in Minnesota. These storms trained across the same areas as well, with some spots experiencing large hail or damaging winds two or three times during the event. In addition, heavy rainfall became a problem, resulting in some flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado wrapped in downburst winds and heavy rain tracked intermittently for about eleven miles. Brick facing and roofing material were torn off a building in Leonard. Numerous large two foot diameter cottonwood and oak trees were blown over or snapped at farmsteads and shelterbelts along and north of highway 46. Peak winds were estimated at 100 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong instability tied to very hot temperatures across Southwest Arkansas and Southeast Oklahoma resulted in the development of severe thunderstorms during the late afternoon and evening hours of August 8th. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By the early morning hours of the 4th, an area of surface low pressure had moved into northeast South Dakota, with a warm front extending out to the east. Surface dew point values north of the front ranged in the lower 60s while south of the front they topped out around 70. At 850 millibars, the low level jet pushed juicy air up into southeast North Dakota and west central Minnesota, with drier air to the north. Finally, forty-five to fifty knot westerly winds at 500 millibars provided ample shear to the system. Thunderstorms over western and central North Dakota proceeded east and moved into Barnes County, North Dakota, during the first few hours of the 4th. These storms tracked nearly due east, finally exiting Wadena County, Minnesota, around sunrise. The strongest storms mainly stayed along and south of Interstate 94 in North Dakota and U. S. Highway 10 in Minnesota. These storms trained across the same areas as well, with some spots experiencing large hail or damaging winds two or three times during the event. In addition, heavy rainfall became a problem, resulting in some flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Lightning ignited a fire that destroyed one restaurant and badly damaged a second neighboring restaurant.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very strong area of low pressure moved northeast across the Central Great Lakes on September 10th. A warm front stretching southeast from this low lifted across northern Ohio causing showers and thunderstorms to develop during the afternoon. At least four weak tornadoes touched down in Summit and Portage Counties. Several funnel clouds were also reported in Wayne County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A very weak EF0 tornado touched down near Streetsboro.  The touch down occurred just south of Lake Rockwell Road to the west of State Route 14.  The tornado was on the ground for about a tenth of a mile and lifted before reaching State Route 14.  The tornado downed one tree and tore the branches off a couple other trees.  The damage path was no more than 20 yards in width.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Warm moist air ahead of a slow moving cold front supported storms with torrential rain June 23rd through midday on the 25th. Numerous thunderstorms produced rainfall amounts around 1 to 2 inches during that time. For areas that saw training thunderstorms rainfall amounts exceeded 4 inches.  Heavy rain and floods the week before had kept grounds saturated in many areas, so this additional rainfall was sufficient to cause flash floods.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rainfall around 2 to 4 inches fell over Lorain County on the evening of June 25th. The first round of showers began from 3 to 5 p.m. and was the  heaviest from 7 to 9 p.m. The highest amount measured was 3.72 inches in Elyria. This resulted in significant flooding to the area with numerous homes inundated. In Elyria about 8:55 p.m., a manhole cover popped off on Gulf Road, leaving a hole big enough for a submarine, a dispatchers transmission said. At 9:20 p.m., state Route 57 north between state Route 254 and Schadden Road in Elyria was blocked off, said police Lt. Lee Frank. Martin's Run Creek in Lorain caused flooding of several streets between West 35th Street and Oberlin Avenue. The Oberlin Police Department confirmed there were areas of flooding all throughout the city of Oberlin. Oberlin streets were blocked in many areas because of high water, including Prospect Street, North Main Street and South Professor Street.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed across Ohio on June 11th ahead of a low pressure system located near Chicago. Instability was fairly low but enhanced winds moving through an upper level trough aloft resulted in a severe thunderstorm producing damaging winds that tracked from near Youngstown in Mahoning County to Hubbard in Trumbull County. Numerous trees were uprooted with this storm. Damage was also reported in Mill Creek Metropark where several roads were closed due to downed trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees and power lines down in Mill Creek MetroPark and across Youngstown. Some trees were uprooted. The following roads were closed due to downed trees; West Golf Drive, East Park Drive, Chestnut Hill, West Drive, East Glacier, Valley Drive, and the Flats Area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Areas of moderate to heavy rainfall fell across the Rio Grande Valley and Deep South Texas during the last few days of the month, but the effects would not be felt during the month of August.  Little rainfall during the middle of the month allowed for drought conditions to worsen across portions of the area, with severe (D2) drought conditions returning once again to Zapata County and increasing in coverage across Kenedy County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: While periods of moderate to heavy rainfall fell during the last few days of the month, the effects would not be seen during the month of August.  The general lack of rainfall during the middle of the month allowed drought conditions to intensify across central Kenedy County as severe (D2) drought conditions spread further east and moderate (D1) drought conditions spread further north and eliminated the abnormally dry (D0) area in the far NW corner of the county.  Moderate (D1) drought conditions remained along the southern country border and extreme (D3) drought conditions remained across coastal Kenedy County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An active monsoon pattern that characterized July 2014 continued into August, with an especially wet period during the first several days of the month. Widespread heavy rain eased from the 6th through 8th, however, as more typical isolated to scattered thunderstorms dominated the landscape from the 9th through 12th.  A monsoon burst, aided by a subtropical low pressure system aloft, brought heavy rain and local flash flooding on the 13th and 14th. Drier air worked into the northwest parts of the state with much less storm activity from the 15th into the 21st. Another good surge of monsoon moisture from the south arrived late on the 21st with widespread showers and storms on the 22nd, some with heavy rain and flash flooding. The 23rd was much drier then a gradual increase in moisture returned on the 24th and continued into the 27th. The 26th was an active day with a few reports of significant flash flooding. The remainder of the month turned much drier and warmer.  Despite the active monsoon,  New Mexico's rangeland and pastures were rated 56% very poor to poor at the beginning of the month,  with  only modest improvements during the month. Despite short-term gains,  longer-term hydrological impacts (below-normal reservoir levels) remained after multiple years of below-normal snowpack. The Middle Rio Grande Conservancy District curtailed water bank deliveries for irrigation in response to low flows along the Rio Grande during the month. The combination of short- and long-term hydrological impacts, below-normal mountain snowpack conditions in the headwater regions led to the re-introduction of an area of Moderate Drought (D1) in the Middle Rio Grande corridor from Socorro County northward to Sante Fe County.

A potent upper-level storm system impacted the region on Sunday, July 27th, bringing several rounds of severe weather along with locally heavy rainfall. Three tornadoes were observed across east Tennessee; one classified as a strong, EF-3 tornado with winds of 140 mph. Additionally, there were several reports of straight-line wind damage and large hail up 2 to 3 inches in diameter! A storm system of this magnitude is highly unusual for this time of year due to the strength of the front and the record cool temperatures it produced in the middle of the Summer season.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An EF3 tornado with estimated winds between 140 and 150 mph with a path length of 1.81 miles and 800 yard width, uprooted numerous trees and snapped several along the entire path. Structural damage varied from minor to major with the most significant damage noted in the Speedwell area near the end of the track.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level low pressure system tracked southeastward from the St. Louis area through the Mid-South on August 17th-18th, 2014. The upper level low interacted with daytime heating to produce showers and thunderstorms across the area during the afternoon and evening hours on both days. Some storms became severe producing large hail and flash flooding. The storms diminished after sunset due to the loss of daytime heating.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Slow moving thunderstorms produced some flash flooding across Eastern Lauderdale County. Highway 209 between Gates and Halls was closed due to flash flooding as well as Highway 19 near Durhamville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: There was a cold front near the Pecos River on the eleventh which provided a source of convergence and lift.  This front shifted north over the central and northern Permian Basin as well as southeast New Mexico that night.  The atmosphere was very moist and unstable.  There were weak winds aloft which allowed for slower moving storms and rain contributing to flash flooding.  Another cold front moved through the area on the twelfth.  Upper level disturbances were also over the region which allowed for more atmospheric lift.  These conditions combined to produce flash flooding across southeast New Mexico and West Texas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain moved across Eddy County and produced flash flooding near Artesia.  A storm spotter reported one foot of water running over U.S. 285 north of Artesia.  The cost of damage is a very rough estimate.

Upper level disturbances were also over the region which allowed for more atmospheric lift.  These conditions combined to produce flash flooding across southeast New Mexico and West Texas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain fell across Eddy County and produced flash flooding in Artesia.  Twentieth and Thirteenth streets in Artesia were reported to be flooded with water over the curbs.  The cost of damage is a very rough estimate.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: During the afternoon and evening of September 9, 2014 a line of thunderstorms moved though eastern Nebraska into Iowa and northern Missouri. Along the southwestern edge of the line a strong supercell formed, producing widespread wind and hail across far northwestern Missouri. This supercell went on to produce 5 brief and weak tornadoes across northwestern Missouri before finally dissipating. The main line of convection then caused wind damage across northern Missouri through the remainder of the overnight hours. Another tornado then formed early in the morning on September 10 near Kirksville, Missouri. This tornado moved into the town and caused some minor damage to trees and residences. Once the wind and tornado threat decreased widespread heavy rain, producing up to 10 inches in some areas, caused flooding and flash flooding across much of northern Missouri, including closures to several main highways. No injuries were reported as a result of the severe weather and flooding, but the far northern part of the state received much damage on account of the winds and flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several areas across Nodaway County received several inches of rain, which led to many roads being impassible for a short time near Barnard, Skidmore, Arkoe, and Burlington Junction.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rain changed to snow from northwest to southeast as temperatures fell in the wake of an arctic cold front. A short period of freezing rain and sleet occurred during the transition. Along and north of a line from Cape Girardeau to Van Buren, a total of 1 to 3 inches fell, except up to 4 inches around Perryville. The snow fell heavily at times around Perryville, reducing visibility to as low as one-quarter mile at times. Snowfall rates were around an inch per hour. Some specific snowfall accumulations included 4 inches at Perryville (Perry County), 2 inches at Clearwater Dam (Wayne County), 1 inch at Cape Girardeau, 1 inch at Marble Hill (Bollinger County), and 1 inch at Lake Wappapello (Wayne County). A low pressure system tracked northeast from central Arkansas across the Lower Ohio Valley. Rain changed to snow on the northwest side of the low track.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large winter storm dumped anywhere from 6 to as much as 14 inches of snow across much of eastern Kansas.  The bulk of the snow fell during February 4th spreading from the southwest to the northeast during the pre-dawn hours of February 4th.  The snow was steady and became heavy at times.  The snow ended from west to east after sunset on the 4th and lingered just past midnight on the 5th across extreme eastern Kansas.  The heaviest snow band fell roughly along I-70 from Salina east through Manhattan through Topeka and into west Kansas City.  Many of those areas received 10-14 inches of snow.  The 24 hour snow totals ranked in the top 5 in many of the cities mentioned above.  Impacts were felt in travel especially late on February 4th as strong north winds caused blowing and drifting.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Lyon County received 5 to 7 inches of snow with the heaviest across the northern half of the county.  Neosho River measured 6.5 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another shot of arctic air poured into West Virginia on the 27th.  A clear night with diminishing winds resulted in temperatures well below zero over northern counties to around zero in the southern counties.||The coldest temperatures at dawn on the 28th from the official cooperative network was 13 degrees below zero from Snowshoe.  Middlebourne and Sandyville observed minus 12.  Harrisville saw its temperature drop to 11 below zero, while West Union observed minus 9.  Rock Cave reported a minimum temperature of minus 7.  Readings of minus 6 and minus 7 were seen around Elkins and Glady.  ||Dawn on the 29th was another very cold morning. Temperatures were colder in southern counties than the previous dawn.  Preliminary data indicated the coldest temperature from the official cooperative observers network was 18 below zero from northeast of Sandyville of northern Jackson County.  Middleboure of Tyler County and Mt Nebo of Nicholas County were not  far behind with 16 below zero. West Union observed 14 below zero,  Rosedale of Braxton County had minus 13, while Elkins, Buckhannon, and Spencer had minus 12.  The cooperative observers at Clarksburg, Sissonville, and Grantsville all observed minus 10.  Glenville and Pineville had minus 9.  Charleston reached down to minus 5, the coldest reading there since February of 1996.  Oceana of Wyoming County also observed 5 below zero.| |Some unofficial readings included, minus 11 at Jane Lew, minus 10 at Lakin in Mason County, and minus 7 at Beech Fork in Wayne County.||Dawn on the 30th was another cold morning, with the coldest readings finally shifting into the deep mountain valleys. Glady reported 18 degrees below zero.  Marlinton observed 15 below zero, while Elkins had minus 11.  An unofficial reading of 17 below zero was measured at Green Bank.||The 3 day cold wave finally ended as temperatures moderated during the sunny afternoon of Thursday the 30th.

The South Central Texas counties that most needed rain generally didnt get it in July. Most of the area that was in Severe Drought Category (D2) or worse at the beginning of the month had 75 percent of normal rainfall or less in July. This meant that Blanco County worsened to Stage D2 joining Bandera, Edwards, Kendall, Kerr, Llano, and Medina Counties. Gillespie and Val Verde Counties remained in Extreme Category (D3). Fire danger was moderate to high across the area at the end of July.  Of the counties in D2 or worse drought Kerr and Val Verde had burn bans remaining in effect and Blanco, Kendall, Llano, and Medina Counties instituted them during the month. The Texas Crop and Weather Report issued by Texas A&M Agricultural indicated hot and dry weather continued to decrease topsoil and subsoil moisture. Pasture and forage grasses were suffering from moisture stress. Hay fields were no longer growing, and after the first cutting, hay grazer fields needed rain to make a second cutting. Livestock remained in fair condition. The seven day stream flow averages at the end of the month were below normal (10-24 percent) for the Guadalupe, Upper San Antonio, and Upper Colorado River basins. |Area lakes and reservoirs continued well below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was 41.8 feet below normal. Lake Travis dropped nearly two feet to 54 feet below normal. Medina Lake dropped again and was 86 feet below normal. The Edwards Aquifer dropped during the month and was at 633.8 feet which was 5.1 feet lower than the beginning of the month and 7.6 feet below the level at the end of July 2013. The Edwards Aquifer Authority declared stage 4 water restrictions requiring large water users to reduce pumping by 40%. Fredericksburg remained in stage 3 water restrictions, Kerrville moved into stage 2, and Del Rio remained in stage 1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold air was trapped over the inner channels from Fri Nov 28 through Sun Nov 30 due to blocking high pressure. Heavy snow began as warm moist air moved over the area as the block broke down. Weak surface low pressure developed over the Eastern Gulf of Alaska as the arctic front moved northward into the Yukon.  A second snow event occurred on Dec 1, but the amounts were not as heavy as on the 30th. No damage or power outages were reported, but snow removal was a challenge due to this being the first measurable snowfall of the 2014-2015 season.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hyder COOP got 12 inches of new snow on Sunday Nov 30th.

CZ_NAME: INNER CHANNELS FROM KUPREANOF ISLAND TO ETOLIN ISLAND
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rapid development took place well SW of Dixon Entrance on Wed Nov 5. The storm center deepened to 970 MB just off Dixon Entrance Wednesday afternoon then rapidly weakened over land to 986 MB near Cape Spencer later that evening. Marine storm force winds were common with this system with hurricane force gusts. Land winds gusted as high as 92 MPH and caused damage particularly in Ketchikan with one roof blown away with trees down and power outages.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Peak gusts to 55 KT were observed at Cape Decision at 1500. The only part of the zone affected was Kuiu Island. Spotter report from Point Baker: sustained wind 35 to 40 mph with gusts to 50 mph reported around 1400. No damage reported.

CZ_NAME: JUNEAU BOROUGH AND NORTHERN ADMIRALTY ISLAND
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An arctic high to 1042 MB built over Yukon to create strong northerly to northeasterly flow across the area. Cross-barrier outflow winds occurred in the Taku-exposed areas of Juneau and Douglas Island. Critical level was of borderline strength, but a high-level  trough moved south across the region to assist in driving the strong local winds. Haines, Skagway and Hyder had strong winds that started Wednesday afternoon/evening.	No damage was reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous gusts in the 60 to 65 mph range were observed in Downtown Juneau and Douglas on the evening of November 26th through all day on the 27th. Peak observations occurred at the South Douglas wind profiler to 64 mph and to 66 mph at the AML site. No damage was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong northwest flow aloft was present across the Southern Plains and Lower Mississippi valley during this period. A disturbance moved southward out of this flow into the Four State Region. Strong mid level lapse rates and elevated instability resulted in the development of strong to severe thunderstorms during the predawn hours of October 6th. The storms eventually developed into a Mesoscale Convective Complex producing large hail and widespread wind damage across portions of Southeast Oklahoma, Southwest Arkansas as well as Northeast Texas and Northwest Louisiana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees were downed throughout the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong pre-frontal squall line crossed the area late morning through mid afternoon. Strong wind shear and helicity promoted rotation cells as well as bowing line segments. One comma-head storm formed along the Interstate 10 corridor near Live Oak, and this cell raced eastward toward Jacksonville. The storm had a long-lived mesocylone, and the rear flank downdraft descended downward several times causing brief periods of strong low level rotation which caused a few tornado touchdowns. The RFD produced strong winds of 50-80 mph and caused widespread tree damage and some structural damage as the comma-head raced across north Florida, including the Jacksonville metro area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees were blown down in St. Marys, some fell on homes and parked cars. The time of damage was based on radar and timing of wind gusts from area observation stations.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An early season snowfall blanketed southwest Indiana. Snowfall amounts were heaviest in counties along the Ohio River, where anywhere from three to five inches was measured. To the north, Gibson and Pike Counties reported from two to three inches. A weak low pressure system developed over the northern Gulf of Mexico, then moved northeast into Alabama. This system threw moisture northward into unseasonably cold air over the Lower Ohio Valley, resulting in widespread snow. Specific snowfall amounts included 5 inches at Chandler and Newburgh (both in Warrick County), 4 inches at Rockport (Spencer County), 4 inches in Evansville (Vanderburgh County), 4 inches at Mount Vernon (Posey County), 2 inches at Petersburg (Pike County), and 2 inches at Princeton (Gibson County). The snow fell at temperatures right near freezing on relatively warm pavement. The highest accumulations were on grassy areas. Roads were slush-covered and slippery during the period of heaviest snow and immediately after.

An early season snowfall blanketed southwest Indiana. Snowfall amounts were heaviest in counties along the Ohio River, where anywhere from three to five inches was measured. To the north, Gibson and Pike Counties reported from two to three inches. A weak low pressure system developed over the northern Gulf of Mexico, then moved northeast into Alabama. This system threw moisture northward into unseasonably cold air over the Lower Ohio Valley, resulting in widespread snow. Specific snowfall amounts included 5 inches at Chandler and Newburgh (both in Warrick County), 4 inches at Rockport (Spencer County), 4 inches in Evansville (Vanderburgh County), 4 inches at Mount Vernon (Posey County), 2 inches at Petersburg (Pike County), and 2 inches at Princeton (Gibson County). The snow fell at temperatures right near freezing on relatively warm pavement. The highest accumulations were on grassy areas. Roads were slush-covered and slippery during the period of heaviest snow and immediately after.

A majority of central and northern New Mexico received below normal precipitation during April 2014.  As a result,  severe (D2) or worse drought conditions expanded areawide and worsened for parts of the far east, central and west.  An estimated 86 percent of the state was classified in severe drought or worse at the end of April,  as compared to 65 per cent at the beginning of the month.  Exceptional drought (D4) returned to far eastern New Mexico from the Clovis area north to Tucumcari and Clayton.

A strong winter storm brought rain, followed by freezing rain, sleet and snow to portions of western and north central Nebraska. The storm began as rain early in the afternoon on December 14th, and transitioned to freezing rain, sleet, then snow, during the overnight hours and daytime hours on December 15th.  The heaviest snowfall amounts ranged from 4 to 9 inches across north central Nebraska. Freezing rain and sleet caused additional impacts across eastern portions of north central Nebraska, causing very icy roadways.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts across Thomas County ranged from 4 to 6 inches. North winds of 20 to 30 mph increased to 25 to 35 mph with gusts to 45 mph caused blowing and drifting with low visibility during the overnight hours into the morning hours on December 15th. In addition, law enforcement reported multiple accidents on local roadways.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moving up the east coast brought a soaking rain and strong winds to much of southern New England.  The strongest winds were along the east coast of Massachusetts where many trees were still fully leaved.  This resulted in significant tree damage along with power outages. Other strong to severe thunderstorms brought wind damage and flash flooding to much of the rest of Middle Tennessee.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system developed over the northern Gulf of Mexico and intensified as it headed toward the northeast U.S. A coastal low developed along the Atlantic seaboard on November 26th. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: October was another dry month across South Central Texas. Most of the region had less than 50 percent of normal rainfall. The lack of rain had only minor impact on the drought with only Karnes and Lavaca Counties changing to worse category, both to Severe (Stage D2). The rest of our counties remained the same with Medina in Extreme (Stage D3) and Bandera, Bexar, Blanco, Burnet, Comal, De Witt, Edwards, Gillespie, Kendall, Kerr, Llano, Real, and Val Verde in D2. Fire danger was low to moderate across the area at the end of the month.  Of the counties in D2 or worse drought Bexar, Comal, De Witt, Kerr, Medina, and Val Verde had burn bans remaining in effect. The seven day stream flow averages at the end of the month were below normal (10-24 percent) for the Upper Colorado, Upper Guadalupe, and San Antonio River basins. The Lower Colorado, Lower Guadalupe, Medina, Frio, and Nueces River Basins were much below normal (less than 10 percent). Area lakes and reservoirs continued well below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was 32.8 feet below normal. Lake Travis was down slightly at 57.6 feet below normal. Medina Lake dropped again and was 88.6 feet below normal. The Edwards Aquifer rose slightly during the month and was at 629.3 feet. This was 10.7 feet lower than at the end of October 2013 and 34.5 feet below average. The Edwards Aquifer Authority continued stage 4 water restrictions requiring large water users to reduce pumping by 40%. The Barton Springs Edwards Aquifer Conservation District continued stage 2 alarm drought status requiring a 20% reduction in pumping. San Marcos was in stage 4 water restrictions, Fredericksburg and New Braunfels were in stage 3, and Kerrville, San Antonio Water System (SAWS), and Austin were in stage 2.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level trough moved quickly into the Central and Southern Plains providing the necessary lift for scattered strong to severe thunderstorms across Northwest Texas and Western Oklahoma during the evening hours of Sunday, Oct. 12th.  At the surface, a warm front  was rapidly moving northward across East Texas and North Louisiana with low level moisture returning quickly in the wake of the northward moving warm front.  A cold front in association with the upper level trough was rapidly moving eastward through Western Oklahoma and Texas.  Overnight across Southeast Oklahoma, Southwest Arkansas, Northeast Texas and Northwest Louisiana, moderate instability was in place with increasing low and mid-level shear as the upper trough approached from the west. Storms eventually erupted ahead of the cold front across Central Oklahoma and Northern Texas, maturing into a squall line as it approached the region during the predawn hours of Monday, Oct. 13th.  As the squall line traversed through the region, widespread wind damage was reported associated with straight line winds.  Several short track, intense tornadoes developed along the leading edge of the squall line as well across portions of Northeast Texas, Southwest Arkansas and Northern Louisiana.  The storms finally exited the region during the afternoon hours of Oct. 13th.  Post-event Storm Surveys determined that 6 tornadoes occurred with this severe weather outbreak, one of which produced 1 fatality and 4 injuries in Little River County, Arkansas.  Another tornado produced widespread damage across Ouachita Parish in Monroe, Louisiana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were downed across the county including trees blocking Hwys. 84, 2138, 747 South and CRs. 3908 and 3708.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous upper level trough moved out of the Southern Plains and into the Lower Mississippi Valley during the late afternoon and evening hours of October 2nd. This upper level trough took on a negative tilt as it moved towards the Four State Region, with vigorous lift resulting in the development of severe thunderstorms in a moderately unstable environment. Strong unidirectional deep layer shear resulted in the convection eventually taking on the shape of a squall line which raced through the region producing widespread wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A storage shed was struck my lightning and set on fire on Hwy. 3 north of 220.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The California drought continued in full force during the month of October, 2014. Exceptional drought was detected by the U.S. Drought Monitor for almost the entire Central California region. This extent of exceptional drought is extremely unusual for California. The 2013-2014 water year (July 1 - June 30) concluded with Fresno setting its second driest on record (4.81 inches) and Bakersfield setting its third driest (2.41 inches). ||There continues to be significant media coverage on the on-going drought conditions. These reports include discussion of significant re-allocation of water resources from the east to west side of the San Joaquin Valley, farmers forgoing planting of some crops, a decrease in the snow-related tourism activity in the Southern Sierra Nevada, reduction in air quality due to persistent stagnant air, loss or reduction of ground water, wells drying up in several communities leaving them with no water, and an unprecedented increase in fire danger across the Southern Sierra Nevada and Tehachapi Mountains. For the first time on record, red flag warnings were issued in January for not only the Southern Sierra Nevada and the Tehachapi Mountains but also the south end of the San Joaquin Valley.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A majority of central and northern New Mexico received below normal precipitation during April 2014.  As a result,  severe (D2) or worse drought conditions expanded areawide and worsened for parts of the far east, central and west.  An estimated 86 percent of the state was classified in severe drought or worse at the end of April,  as compared to 65 per cent at the beginning of the month.  Exceptional drought (D4) returned to far eastern New Mexico from the Clovis area north to Tucumcari and Clayton.
Drought persisted with minor improvements in the absence of meaningful rainfall.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: D2 (severe) drought was completely removed, leaving only D1 (moderate) and D0 (abnormally dry) drought.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A swell from a low far northwest of the islands caused surf of 10 to 15 feet along the north- and west-facing shores of Niihau and Kauai; along the north-facing shores of Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; and 8 to 12 feet along the west-facing shores of Oahu and Molokai.  There were no reports of significant injuries or property damage.

A swell from a low far northwest of the islands caused surf of 10 to 15 feet along the north- and west-facing shores of Niihau and Kauai; along the north-facing shores of Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; and 8 to 12 feet along the west-facing shores of Oahu and Molokai.  There were no reports of significant injuries or property damage.

Localized instability over the lee side of the Big Island of Hawaii generated heavy showers.  The rain produced small stream and drainage ditch flooding, and ponding on roadways.  There were no reports of significant injuries or property damage.

An upper trough near the eastern end of the Aloha State acted on low level moisture to produce heavy downpours, including isolated thunderstorms.  The results were ponding on roadways, and small stream and drainage ditch flooding.  No serious injuries or property damage were reported.

The first snow of the fall developed and moved across the area.  Most areas received 1 to 3 inches.  However, a narrow area of enhanced snow developed across Stanton county.  Most of Stanton county had 5 to 7 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 7.0 inches was reported at a location 5 miles WNW of Big Bow.

CZ_NAME: INNER WATERS FROM POINT MUGU TO SAN MATEO POINT CA INCLUDING SANTA CATALINA AND ANACAPA ISLANDS
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong and gusty Santa Ana winds impacted the coastal waters off the coast of Ventura county. In one incident, a 15 foot boat was capsized by the strong northeasterly winds. In another incident, a kayaker was blown about 600 yards offshore by the winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong Santa Ana winds impacted the coastal waters just off the Santa Monica Mountains. The north to northeast winds blew a kayaker 600 yards offshore. The kayaker was rescued by the fire department.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The California drought continued in full force during the month of August, 2014. Exceptional drought was detected by the U.S. Drought Monitor for almost the entire Central California region. This extent of exceptional drought is extremely unusual for California. The 2013-2014 water year (July 1 - June 30) concluded with Fresno setting its second driest on record (4.81 inches) and Bakersfield setting its third driest (2.41 inches). ||There continues to be significant media coverage on the on-going drought conditions. These reports include discussion of significant re-allocation of water resources from the east to west side of the San Joaquin Valley, farmers forgoing planting of some crops, a decrease in the snow-related tourism activity in the Southern Sierra Nevada, reduction in air quality due to persistent stagnant air, loss or reduction of ground water, and an unprecedented increase in fire danger across the Southern Sierra Nevada and Tehachapi Mountains. For the first time on record, red flag warnings were issued in January for not only the Southern Sierra Nevada and the Tehachapi Mountains but also the south end of the San Joaquin Valley.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread severe thunderstorms downed numerous trees across a large swath of eastern Kentucky during the afternoon and evening hours of September 2nd. Thunderstorms first began forming along an old outflow boundary just before 4 pm on this date. With the amount of moisture and instability in place, it wasn't long before a number of these storms began producing damaging wind gusts. The last of the storms weakened below severe limits just before 7 pm.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down and onto Rt. 899 between mile markers 7 and 11.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak low level trough extended across the Okefenokee Swamp southward across the Suwanee River Valley, which triggered early morning slow moving showers and thunderstorms across Columbia county. A moisture feed off of the Gulf of Mexico due to low level SSW winds and spokes of energy rotating around a low center meandering over the local area fueled slow moving convection, which caused flash flooding over Columbia county generally between the cities of Columbia and Lake City. Daily storm total amounts ranged from 7 to almost 10.5 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An observer measured 7.88 inches of rainfall since midnight.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Deep layer troughing with WSW upper level flow advected moisture inland form the Gulf of Mexico. This moisture feed combined with daytime instability and a front sagging southward over S Ga triggered heavy rainfall potential across the local forecast area. PWAT values were 2.17 to 2.19 inches, and some cells trained across local areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Street flooding was reported in the Hogans Creek area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front sweeping across the lower Great Lakes was preceded and accompanied by severe thunderstorms. The thunderstorm winds produced widespread damage throughout the region. Trees and power lines were downed. The highest recorded gust was 66 mph at Fort Drum. Some specific reports of damage included:  trees down on Route 5 in Portland, Rockspring Road in Ashord, Old Chautauqua Road in Gerry, Allen Street in South Dayton, Boston-Colden Road in Colden, Route 20 in Pavilion, and Locust Street in Honeoye. Some of the trees were measured to 30 inches in diameter. The falling trees and limbs damaged several homes and automobiles in Marion, Scriba, West Rush and Martinsburg. In Farmington, a stretch of ten power poles was blown over by the strong winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Law enforcement reported trees and wires down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong thunderstorms developed to the southeast of the greater Phoenix area during the afternoon hours on July 3rd, and they produced gusty outflow winds in excess of 50 mph. The outflow winds spread to the northwest and into the south central deserts during the evening hours. In addition to bringing dense blowing dust to the deserts, the outflow winds led to additional thunderstorm development. Isolated to scattered evening thunderstorms then produced gusty and damaging winds across portions of the greater Phoenix area, and also generated locally heavy rain which led to flooding of washes, roads and low lying areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms with gusty and damaging outflow winds developed across portions of the greater Phoenix area during the evening hours on July 3rd. According to a trained weather spotter, wind gusts estimated to be nearly 60 mph produced roof and shingle damage to a residence near McDowell Avenue and State Route 51.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed across portions of southwest Arizona during the afternoon hours on July 5th, and they affected both Yuma and La Paz counties, including the community of Yuma. The storms produced gusty and damaging outflow winds in excess of 50 mph, which were sufficient to blow down power poles. The storms also produced locally heavy rainfall which led to significant flooding in the community of Ligurta. The heavy rain also led to the issuance of Small Stream Flood Advisories as well as Flash Flood Warnings.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong thunderstorms developed across far southwest Arizona during the afternoon hours on July 5th and they affected the communities of Yuma and Martinez lake. The storms generated strong and gusty outflow winds; a mesonet  station located 4 miles southeast of Martinez Lake measured a wind gust to 59 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An active monsoon pattern that characterized July 2014 continued into August, with an especially wet period during the first several days of the month. Widespread heavy rain eased from the 6th through 8th, however, as more typical isolated to scattered thunderstorms dominated the landscape from the 9th through 12th.  A monsoon burst, aided by a subtropical low pressure system aloft, brought heavy rain and local flash flooding on the 13th and 14th. Drier air worked into the northwest parts of the state with much less storm activity from the 15th into the 21st. Another good surge of monsoon moisture from the south arrived late on the 21st with widespread showers and storms on the 22nd, some with heavy rain and flash flooding. The 23rd was much drier then a gradual increase in moisture returned on the 24th and continued into the 27th. The 26th was an active day with a few reports of significant flash flooding. The remainder of the month turned much drier and warmer.  Despite the active monsoon,  New Mexico's rangeland and pastures were rated 56% very poor to poor at the beginning of the month,  with  only modest improvements during the month. Despite short-term gains,  longer-term hydrological impacts (below-normal reservoir levels) remained after multiple years of below-normal snowpack. The Middle Rio Grande Conservancy District curtailed water bank deliveries for irrigation in response to low flows along the Rio Grande during the month. The combination of short- and long-term hydrological impacts, below-normal mountain snowpack conditions in the headwater regions led to the re-introduction of an area of Moderate Drought (D1) in the Middle Rio Grande corridor from Socorro County northward to Sante Fe County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The remnants of Tropical Storm Odile and an associated mid-level circulation were still over the region.  The airmass was very moist, and lift was enhanced by upslope low-level winds across southeast New Mexico and the higher terrain of West Texas.  These conditions resulted in rain and thunderstorms across the area, and flash flooding continued as moderate to heavy rain moved over areas with previously saturated soils.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain fell across Martin County and produced flash flooding.  A truck driver reported that water was so high on State Highway 137 just north of Farm to Market Road 846 in Martin County that he was barely able to make it through the water.  The cost of damage is a very rough estimate.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain fell across Borden County and produced flash flooding.  Most of the farm to market roads across eastern Borden County had flooding.  Farm to Market roads 1610, 1205 and 669 were closed due to flooding.  The cost of damage is a very rough estimate.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By the early morning hours of the 4th, an area of surface low pressure had moved into northeast South Dakota, with a warm front extending out to the east. Surface dew point values north of the front ranged in the lower 60s while south of the front they topped out around 70. At 850 millibars, the low level jet pushed juicy air up into southeast North Dakota and west central Minnesota, with drier air to the north. Finally, forty-five to fifty knot westerly winds at 500 millibars provided ample shear to the system. Thunderstorms over western and central North Dakota proceeded east and moved into Barnes County, North Dakota, during the first few hours of the 4th. These storms tracked nearly due east, finally exiting Wadena County, Minnesota, around sunrise. The strongest storms mainly stayed along and south of Interstate 94 in North Dakota and U. S. Highway 10 in Minnesota. These storms trained across the same areas as well, with some spots experiencing large hail or damaging winds two or three times during the event. In addition, heavy rainfall became a problem, resulting in some flash flooding.

Areas of moderate to heavy rainfall fell across the Rio Grande Valley and Deep South Texas during the last few days of the month, but the effects would not be felt during the month of August.  Little rainfall during the middle of the month allowed for drought conditions to worsen across portions of the area, with severe (D2) drought conditions returning once again to Zapata County and increasing in coverage across Kenedy County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: While periods of moderate to heavy rainfall fell during the last few days of the month, the effects would not be felt during the month of August.  Severe (D2) drought conditions spread further east, fully encompassing the western half of the county, while moderate (D1) drought conditions increased in coverage taking over much of the eastern half of the county, with only a small sliver of abnormally dry (D0) conditions remaining on the eastern country border.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers and thunderstorms developed during the mid and late afternoon hours on Monday, August 11th, near and south of a weak surface boundary that was reinforced south from storms that developed the previous day. This large boundary extended along the Interstate 20 corridor of North Central and East Texas into North Louisiana, with strong daytime heating atop a very moist air mass contributing to moderate instability, resulting in shower and thunderstorm development. These storms produced numerous outflow boundaries across North Louisiana, which allowed for these storms to become more widespread and form a small mesoscale convective system, as they accelerated south across North Central Louisiana. Damaging winds were noted at times, resulting in downed trees and power lines over the area. A second cluster of showers and thunderstorms developed over East Central Texas south of the stationary outflow boundary, and quickly spread east southeast across East Texas south of Interstate 20. Some of these storms also became severe over Nacogdoches, Shelby, and Sabine counties, where downbursts downed numerous trees over these areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were downed across the entire county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed in a moderately unstable airmass along the lake breeze boundary that extended across the lower Genesee Valley and Western Finger Lakes. The thunderstorms produced damaging winds that downed trees and wires in Greece and Newark. Hail also fell from the storms: one-inch hail reported in Rochester and three-quarter-inch hail covered the ground in Newark. The heavy rains that fell resulted in urban flooding. Storm sewers were not able to keep up in the intense rainfall with streets closed in Newark and Greece.

No fatalities occurred with this lightning strike, but one student who was closest to the strike suffered significant injuries and was in the hospital for over a week.

A wildfire caused from lightning from August 11th expanded into a complex of fires that was finally contained in October.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Deception Creek fire complex was started by multiple lightning storms on Aug 11, 2014. The fire complex included the Deception Creek, Staley, Davey, Pool, Spirit and Edith fires. The fire was approximately 7,800 burning in heavy timber. At times, the fire came close to structures near the community of Oakridge, OR.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A human caused wildfire burned around 5,520 acres in the Mount Hood and Clackamas National Forests near Estacada, Oregon. The fire was finally contained in October.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The 36 Pit Wildfire resulted in evacuations of a RV park and closures of several camp grounds and recreational areas near Estacada, OR. A 5-mile stretch of Highway 224 was closed, as well as some local roads and trails.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An arctic air mass settled over the region during much of the week between Tuesday, January 21st and Friday, January 24th. Very cold air in place allowed for daytime high temperatures only in the single digits and teens and readings frequently below zero at night. With a persistent west to northwest breeze, wind chill values dropped to dangerously cold levels in the night time and morning hours. Wind chill values were -10 to -20 degrees over many areas, with wind chill readings as low as -25 degrees over the high terrain of the southern Green Mountains. The most widespread lowest values occurred on the early morning of Wednesday, January 22nd.  Temperatures finally moderated and wind became light by the end of the week, ending the dangerously low wind chill values.

Wind chill values were -10 to -25 degrees over many areas, with wind chill readings as low as -35 degrees over the high terrain of the Adirondacks.  The most widespread lowest values occurred on the early morning of Wednesday, January 22nd.  This long duration period of frigid arctic air resulted in shelters being opened across the region for the homeless.  Temperatures finally moderated and wind became light by the end of the week, ending the dangerously low wind chill values.

North to northwest winds gusting to 45 to 55 mph combined with several inches of fresh powdery snow on the ground to produce whiteout conditions in open country. Conditions also deteriorated in some sections of the larger cities, which had not happened with the other blizzard events of the winter to date. Interstate 94 was closed from Bismarck through the Fargo-Moorhead area to Alexandria. Interstate 29 was closed throughout all of eastern North Dakota, U. S. Highway 2 was closed from East Grand Forks to Crookston, and U. S. Highway 10 was closed from Moorhead to Detroit Lakes. Some schools were delayed or cancelled on the 27th, as roads were just starting to be plowed. A Winnipeg man was struck and killed on Interstate 29 near Pembina when he stopped to check an accident scene.

CZ_NAME: SANTA CLARA VALLEY INCLUDING SAN JOSE
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong wind storm struck the Bay Area on December 30 during the afternoon and evening hours. Strong winds brought down numerous trees and power lines across the area. The combination of recent heavy rains earlier in the month brought weakened ground conditions and then there were numerous dead trees across the area from years of ongoing drought. Major disruptions to the evening commute due to downed trees and the accidents they caused were observed. Wind gusts of 40-55 MPH were widespread across the area. Despite most areas not reaching 60 MPH, there was widespread wind damage and impacts due to the reasons above.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong front brought strong winds to the Oregon coast as well as South Central Oregon east of the Cascades.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The METAR at Gold Beach recorded a gust to 59 mph at 12/0219 PST.  The ODOT sensor at Humbug Mountain recorded a gust to 59 mph at 12/0648 PST and a gust to 60 mph at 12/0718 PST. A spotter at Gold Beach reported sustained winds of 56 mph at 12/0404  PST.

Several Winter Storm Warning and Winter Weather Advisories were issued for this system.  Snow amounts in inches are as followed: (5) west of Hermiston, (4) at NWS Pendleton, (5) southwest of Heppner, (9) in Condon, (5) in Weston, (4) at Irrigon, (4) in Milton-Freewater, (4) in Hermiston, (6) south southwest of Chenoweth, (4) in John Day, (4) in Monument, (4) in Redmond, (5) west southwest of Mitchell, (11) and in Camp Sherman.

A low pressure system intensified as it tracked east across the central Rockies.  The winter storm produced moderate to heavy snow and gusty north to northeast winds of 25 to 35 mph.  Considerable blowing and drifting snow and very low visibilities created significant impacts to holiday travel across southeast Wyoming.  Interstate 80 was closed for several hours west of Rawlins and between Cheyenne and Laramie due to multiple vehicle accidents.  Snow accumulations varied from four to 14 inches, heavies over the southern Laramie Range and foothills.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Five to nine inches of snow was reported, heaviest northeast of Rawlins.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rain changed to snow from northwest to southeast as temperatures fell in the wake of an arctic cold front. A short period of freezing rain and sleet occurred during the transition. Along and north of a line from Cape Girardeau to Van Buren, a total of 1 to 3 inches fell, except up to 4 inches around Perryville. The snow fell heavily at times around Perryville, reducing visibility to as low as one-quarter mile at times. Snowfall rates were around an inch per hour. Some specific snowfall accumulations included 4 inches at Perryville (Perry County), 2 inches at Clearwater Dam (Wayne County), 1 inch at Cape Girardeau, 1 inch at Marble Hill (Bollinger County), and 1 inch at Lake Wappapello (Wayne County). A low pressure system tracked northeast from central Arkansas across the Lower Ohio Valley. Rain changed to snow on the northwest side of the low track.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system brought heavy snow to the North Central Mountains, then brought strong winds and heavy snow to the northeast plains of Colorado.  In the mountains, storm totals included:  15 inches at Cabin Creek; 12.5 inches, 3 miles east-northeast of Tabernash; 12 inches at Winter Park, 11 inches at Rawah SNOTEL; 10 inches at Echo Lake; 8 inches at Deadman Hill and Willow Park.  Across the northeast plains of Colorado, storm totals included:  9 inches in Peetz; 8 inches in Brush and 5 miles west-southwest of Leroy; 7 inches at Fort Morgan, 4 miles west-northwest of Iliff and Sterling; 6.5 inches, 4 miles northwest of Elizabeth; 6 inches, 11 miles south-southeast of Haxtun and Woodrow; 5 inches, 21 miles north of New Raymer; with 4 inches in Julesburg.  In Peetz, strong winds produced snow drifts, up to 4 feet deep.

An intense low pressure that passed east of New Jersey on the 2nd combined with an approaching high pressure system to bring more strong (northwest) winds into New Jersey mainly during the morning of the 2nd. The strongest winds occurred along coastal areas and the higher terrain of the state where peak wind gusts averaged around 50 mph. Elsewhere in the state, peak wind gusts averaged around 40 mph. These strong winds knocked down weak tree limbs and wires and caused isolated power outages. The tree limb damage was exacerbated by many trees still having leaves as October was unseasonably warm.  Atlantic City Electric reported about 5,000 homes and businesses lost power with Egg Harbor Township (Atlantic County) hardest hit. Peak wind gusts included 50 mph in Wantage (Sussex County), Tuckerton (Ocean County) and West Cape May (Cape May County), 48 mph in Harvey Cedars (Ocean County), 47 mph in Barnegat (Ocean County), 46 mph in Atlantic City (Atlantic County), 43 mph in Lumberton (Burlington County), 41 mph in Millville (Cumberland County) and 40 mph in Trenton (Mercer County).  A developing low pressure over the Carolinas moved offshore on the morning of November 1st. As it passed east of Cape Hatteras, North Carolina during the early evening of November 1st, the pressure gradient (difference) between it and a high pressure system in the Mississippi Valley started to increase and winds became stronger. This pressure difference over New Jersey maximized during the morning of the 2nd. At 7 a.m. EST on November 2nd, the low pressure system was well east of the New Jersey coast and as it reached the coastal waters east of Massachusetts that afternoon, strong winds ceased across the state.

Another shot of arctic air poured into West Virginia on the 27th.  A clear night with diminishing winds resulted in temperatures well below zero over northern counties to around zero in the southern counties.||The coldest temperatures at dawn on the 28th from the official cooperative network was 13 degrees below zero from Snowshoe.  Middlebourne and Sandyville observed minus 12.  Harrisville saw its temperature drop to 11 below zero, while West Union observed minus 9.  Rock Cave reported a minimum temperature of minus 7.  Readings of minus 6 and minus 7 were seen around Elkins and Glady.  ||Dawn on the 29th was another very cold morning. Temperatures were colder in southern counties than the previous dawn.  Preliminary data indicated the coldest temperature from the official cooperative observers network was 18 below zero from northeast of Sandyville of northern Jackson County.  Middleboure of Tyler County and Mt Nebo of Nicholas County were not  far behind with 16 below zero. West Union observed 14 below zero,  Rosedale of Braxton County had minus 13, while Elkins, Buckhannon, and Spencer had minus 12.  The cooperative observers at Clarksburg, Sissonville, and Grantsville all observed minus 10.  Glenville and Pineville had minus 9.  Charleston reached down to minus 5, the coldest reading there since February of 1996.  Oceana of Wyoming County also observed 5 below zero.| |Some unofficial readings included, minus 11 at Jane Lew, minus 10 at Lakin in Mason County, and minus 7 at Beech Fork in Wayne County.||Dawn on the 30th was another cold morning, with the coldest readings finally shifting into the deep mountain valleys. Glady reported 18 degrees below zero.  Marlinton observed 15 below zero, while Elkins had minus 11.  An unofficial reading of 17 below zero was measured at Green Bank.||The 3 day cold wave finally ended as temperatures moderated during the sunny afternoon of Thursday the 30th.

A long lasting snowstorm occurring across all of eastern upstate New York between the evening of New Years Day and the morning of January 3rd, 2014.  ||A slow moving frontal boundary situated over the mid-Atlantic Region was in place on Wednesday, January 1st.  An area of high pressure situated over southern Quebec allowed Arctic air to move down into the region.  As a weak wave of low pressure developed along the front, moisture moved up and over the frontal boundary into the region. As a result, light snow broke out and gradually spread from south to north between the evening on Wednesday, January 1st and the early morning hours on Thursday, January 2nd. The snow evolved into a moderate snow over portions of the Mohawk Valley, Schoharie Valley and Capital Region during the morning hours on January 2nd and continued through much of the day.  Further south, there was a brief break in the steady snowfall during the daytime on January 2nd, but it remained quite cold, with temperatures only in the single digits over much of the region. ||On the evening of Thursday, January 2nd, a new area of low pressure began to form of the mid-Atlantic coast.  This brought some moisture from the Atlantic Ocean into the region, and a moderate snowfall developed over the entire area.  The snow gradually tapered off to light snow and snow showers from west to east overnight as the low pressure area tracked east northeast away from the region.  By the morning hours of Friday, January 3rd, a general 6 to 12 inches of snow fell over much of the region, with lighter amounts across the far western Adirondacks and the mid-Hudson valley region.  A few spots in the high terrain of the northern Catskills and Helderbergs saw close to 15 inches.  In addition, temperatures remained very cold and with a cold northwest wind, wind chill values were zero to minus 20 degrees.

In the midst of a long duration snow event, northerly winds transported very cold air into the region from Canada early in the morning hours on Friday, January 3rd.  With winds picking up due to a strengthening area of low pressure off the eastern seaboard, wind chill values became dangerously low. Wind chill values dropped below -15 degrees by Friday morning over much of the region. ||Wind chill values remained very low, even behind the storm through the day on Friday. With very cold temperatures continuing on Friday night, wind chill values continued to be -15 to -30 degrees in many locations. Winds finally became calm by early Saturday morning on January 4th, although the frigid temperatures continued to make for dangerous conditions.

An arctic air mass settled over the region during much of the week between Tuesday, January 21st and Friday, January 24th.  Very cold air in place allowed for daytime high temperatures only in the single digits and teens and readings frequently below zero at night. With a persistent west to northwest breeze, wind chill values dropped to dangerously cold levels in the night time and morning hours.  Wind chill values were -10 to -25 degrees over many areas, with wind chill readings as low as -35 degrees over the high terrain of the Adirondacks.  The most widespread lowest values occurred on the early morning of Wednesday, January 22nd.  This long duration period of frigid arctic air resulted in shelters being opened across the region for the homeless.  Temperatures finally moderated and wind became light by the end of the week, ending the dangerously low wind chill values.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong northwest flow aloft was present across the Southern Plains and Lower Mississippi valley during this period. A disturbance moved southward out of this flow into the Four State Region. Strong mid level lapse rates and elevated instability resulted in the development of strong to severe thunderstorms during the predawn hours of October 6th. The storms eventually developed into a Mesoscale Convective Complex producing large hail and widespread wind damage across portions of Southeast Oklahoma, Southwest Arkansas as well as Northeast Texas and Northwest Louisiana.

CZ_NAME: FERNANDINA BEACH TO ST AUGUSTINE FL OUT 20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong pre-frontal squall line crossed the area late morning through mid afternoon. Strong wind shear and helicity promoted rotation cells as well as bowing line segments. One comma-head storm formed along the Interstate 10 corridor near Live Oak, and this cell raced eastward toward Jacksonville. The storm had a long-lived mesocylone, and the rear flank downdraft descended downward several times causing brief periods of strong low level rotation which caused a few tornado touchdowns. The RFD produced strong winds of 50-80 mph and caused widespread tree damage and some structural damage as the comma-head raced across north Florida, including the Jacksonville metro area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Navy Fuel Depot NOAA Ports Station measured a wind gust to 54 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong thunderstorms developed due to a boundary collision with the east coast sea breeze over Brevard County. A United States Air Force wind tower in Titusville recorded a severe wind gust as one of the thunderstorms moved towards the Indian River Lagoon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: USAF tower 1012, located near the intersection of South Street (SR-405) and Lane Avenue in Titusville, recorded a 61 mph wind gust out of the northwest as a severe thunderstorm moved over the area.

CZ_NAME: VOLUSIA-BREVARD COUNTY LINE TO SEBASTIAN INLET 0-20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed as numerous boundary collisions took place over Brevard County. Several thunderstorms produced strong wind gusts as they moved offshore from Melbourne to Titusville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong winter storm brought rain, followed by freezing rain, sleet and snow to portions of western and north central Nebraska. The storm began as rain early in the afternoon on December 14th, and transitioned to freezing rain, sleet, then snow, during the overnight hours and daytime hours on December 15th.  The heaviest snowfall amounts ranged from 4 to 9 inches across north central Nebraska. Freezing rain and sleet caused additional impacts across eastern portions of north central Nebraska, causing very icy roadways.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts across Wheeler County ranged from 4 to 6 inches. North winds of 20 to 30 mph increased to 25 to 35 mph with gusts to 45 mph caused blowing and drifting with low visibility during the overnight hours into the daytime hours on December 15th. In addition, law enforcement reported icy roads and blowing snow on local roadways.
