EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level disturbance and tropical moisture combined over Southwest Louisiana to produce heavy rain and flooding. This heavy rainfall event capped the one of the wettest summers on record at the Lake Charles Regional Airport.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A very moist air mass allowed for very high rainfall rates across Calcasieu Parish during the morning of the 30th. Rainfall amounts ranged from 4 to near 8 inches with the majority falling from sunrise to noon. The Lake Charles Regional Airport received 7.87 inches during the event with around 3 inches falling in under an hour. After 8 AM a call was received from an off-duty NWS meteorologist of a car submerged in a ditch along Interstate 210 near Nelson Road. Some cars were unable to pass the high waters along Nelson Road and many other streets in the city. Portions of Interstates 10 and 210 were temporarily closed due to high water. 1 home was flooded near the Nelson Road and Gauthier Road intersection and a apartment complex also flooded along Nelson Road. Multiple other homes were flooded across the city of Lake Charles. 5 homes were flooded along Dogwood Ave and a few homes also flooded in the Hunters Grove Subdivision in Iowa.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On the evening of the 31st a line of severe thunderstorms formed over north central Kansas and moved eastward. As they moved east severe winds gusts up to 70 mph blew down tree limbs and damaged a few structures. As the line moved into eastern Kansas it began to weaken and the severe winds more isolated.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: August was another mainly dry month for South Central Texas. Most of the region had below normal precipitation and much of that area had 50 percent or less than normal. As a result Bandera, Kendall, Kerr, and Medina Counties worsened to extreme drought category (Stage D3) and Bastrop, Bexar, Burnet, Caldwell, Comal, De Witt, Guadalupe, Hays, Real, and Travis moved into severe category (Stage D2). Gillespie and Val Verde remained in Stage D3 while Blanco, Edwards, and Llano continued in Stage D2. Fire danger was moderate to high across the area at the end of August.  Of the counties in D2 or worse drought Blanco, Kendall, Kerr, Llano, Medina, and Val Verde had burn bans remaining in effect and Bexar, Burnet, Caldwell, Comal, De Witt, Guadalupe, Hays, and Travis Counties instituted them during the month. The seven day stream flow averages at the end of the month were below normal (10-24 percent) for the Upper San Antonio, Upper Colorado, Medina, and Frio River basins. The Lower Colorado and Guadalupe River Basins were much below normal (less than 10 percent). Area lakes and reservoirs continued well below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was 41.6 feet below normal. Lake Travis dropped more than three feet to 57.4 feet below normal. Medina Lake dropped again and was 87.1 feet below normal. The Edwards Aquifer dropped during the month and was at 626.4 feet which was 2.5 feet lower than the beginning of the month and 5.1 feet below the level at the end of August 2013. The Edwards Aquifer Authority continued stage 4 water restrictions requiring large water users to reduce pumping by 40%. The Barton Springs Edwards Aquifer Conservation District declared stage 2 alarm drought status requiring a 20% reduction in pumping. San Marcos was in stage 4 water restrictions, Fredericksburg and New Braunfels were in stage 3, Kerrville, San Antonio Water System (SAWS), and Austin were in stage 2, and Del Rio and Seguin were in stage 1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An arctic cold front barreled across eastern Kentucky late Sunday January 5th ushering in what would be the coldest temperatures and wind chills experienced in 20 years. Gusty winds up to 50 mph along the front created a few isolated power outages. Rain falling in advance of the arctic front quickly changed over to snow by midnight Sunday night. By dawn on Monday, many areas had received from 1 to 3 inches of snow, with up to 5 inches on Black Mountain. ||The big story was the cold.  Temperatures by Tuesday morning January 7th ranged from 2 below zero to 9 below zero in the valleys of eastern Kentucky, down to 17 below zero at the top of Black Mountain. Gusty west to northwest winds combined with these temperatures to produce wind chills in the 15 to 30 below range for most locations, with the highest terrain along the Virginia border dropping even lower. The last time there were widespread below zero temperatures in eastern Kentucky was in the middle 1990s.||Several southeast Kentucky counties experienced water outages from the cold that lasted up to a week.  The hardest hit counties were Perry and Floyd.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Interstate 75 was blocked due to an injury accident as a result of a vehicle loosing control on black ice. The injured motorist later died at the hospital.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Local officials reported trees were blown down on East County Road 175 North.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front sweeping across the lower Great Lakes was preceded and accompanied by severe thunderstorms. The thunderstorm winds produced widespread damage throughout the region. Trees and power lines were downed. The highest recorded gust was 66 mph at Fort Drum. Some specific reports of damage included:  trees down on Route 5 in Portland, Rockspring Road in Ashord, Old Chautauqua Road in Gerry, Allen Street in South Dayton, Boston-Colden Road in Colden, Route 20 in Pavilion, and Locust Street in Honeoye. Some of the trees were measured to 30 inches in diameter. The falling trees and limbs damaged several homes and automobiles in Marion, Scriba, West Rush and Martinsburg. In Farmington, a stretch of ten power poles was blown over by the strong winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Law enforcement reported trees and wires down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A surface cold front passed through the region during the afternoon on Thursday, August 7th.  This front was associated with a strong upper level trough, with rather cold temperatures aloft.   As a result, some scattered thunderstorms developed during the afternoon hours and several of the storms produced hail. A few of the storms produced severe hail, especially across the Glens Falls-Saratoga Region.  One of the storms also produced damaging wind gusts as well. The threat for storms ended by the late afternoon, as the cold front pushed south and the upper level trough moved away from the area to the east.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported during a thunderstorm in East Nassau.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Extreme drought (D3) conditions continued across part of southeast Arizona during July. Just a small portion of Graham and Greenlee counties was removed from the extreme drought area because of above average monsoonal rainfall.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extreme drought (D3) category persisted across southern and eastern Pinal, northern and western Graham, extreme northeastern Pima and much of northern Greenlee and Cochise counties through July. A small portion of Graham and Greenlee counties was reduced to the severe (D2) category due to above average rainfall. The remainder of the extreme drought area received either near normal July rainfall or as little as 50 percent of normal. Levels at San Carlos Reservoir continued to fall, bottoming out at close to 1 percent of capacity by the end of the month. Soil moisture remained at less than 20 percent of normal. Ranchers continued to be affected by the depletion of rangeland forage vegetation.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread severe thunderstorms downed numerous trees across a large swath of eastern Kentucky during the afternoon and evening hours of September 2nd. Thunderstorms first began forming along an old outflow boundary just before 4 pm on this date. With the amount of moisture and instability in place, it wasn't long before a number of these storms began producing damaging wind gusts. The last of the storms weakened below severe limits just before 7 pm.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down and across Rte. 299.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An active monsoon pattern that characterized July 2014 continued into August, with an especially wet period during the first several days of the month. Widespread heavy rain eased from the 6th through 8th, however, as more typical isolated to scattered thunderstorms dominated the landscape from the 9th through 12th.  A monsoon burst, aided by a subtropical low pressure system aloft, brought heavy rain and local flash flooding on the 13th and 14th. Drier air worked into the northwest parts of the state with much less storm activity from the 15th into the 21st. Another good surge of monsoon moisture from the south arrived late on the 21st with widespread showers and storms on the 22nd, some with heavy rain and flash flooding. The 23rd was much drier then a gradual increase in moisture returned on the 24th and continued into the 27th. The 26th was an active day with a few reports of significant flash flooding. The remainder of the month turned much drier and warmer.  Despite the active monsoon,  New Mexico's rangeland and pastures were rated 56% very poor to poor at the beginning of the month,  with  only modest improvements during the month. Despite short-term gains,  longer-term hydrological impacts (below-normal reservoir levels) remained after multiple years of below-normal snowpack. The Middle Rio Grande Conservancy District curtailed water bank deliveries for irrigation in response to low flows along the Rio Grande during the month. The combination of short- and long-term hydrological impacts, below-normal mountain snowpack conditions in the headwater regions led to the re-introduction of an area of Moderate Drought (D1) in the Middle Rio Grande corridor from Socorro County northward to Sante Fe County.
Hot and humid air over southern New England was enough to produce diurnal thunderstorms.  A few of these became severe producing both large hail and damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree and wires on Powpow Street and Fern Avenue were downed by thunderstorm winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low level east to southeast flow started bringing in some low level moisture to the region with weak flow in the mid levels. Storms developed over the Sacramento Mountains and moved west onto the lowlands toward Tularosa which caused some localized flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding was reported around the Riata Road area west of Tularosa where water was crossing the road. Drainage ditches along Highway 54 were also filling up.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Residual moisture from Hurricane Odile was getting trapped under a building upper ridge across the Rockies. A weak upper level disturbance came down the east side of this ridge and triggered showers and thunderstorms over the western Sacramento Mountains. Slow storm motion combined with the plentiful moisture led to locally heavy rain and flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Highway 82 was closed just west of the tunnel to Cloudcroft was closed due to a rock slide. A section of road at La Luz Creek crossing was closed as well due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong thunderstorm produced severe marine wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This wind gust was reported south of Baytown.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: While there were a few spotty showers and thunderstorms associated with the seabreeze, little rain fell during the last week of July and drought conditions held steady across the Rio Grande Valley and Deep South Texas.  Severe (D2) drought conditions remained firmly entrenched over much of Starr County and western Hidalgo County, while the remainder of the region was covered by a hodgepodge of moderate (D1) and abnormally dry (D0) drought conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe (D2) drought conditions remained over most of the western third of the county. The middle third of the county experienced moderate (D1) drought conditions and the eastern third remained abnormally dry (D0).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Some much welcome and beneficial rain fell across the northern ranchlands and the western brush country the first few days of August, with some areas receiving over 3 inches. This rainfall while helpful, only maintained drought conditions in the areas where it fell.    By the end of the first week of August, Severe (D2) drought conditions began to spread north and east across Hidalgo County and into Kenedy, Brooks, and Jim Hogg counties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Little rain fell during the first week of August across Hidalgo County allowing drought conditions to worsen. Severe (D2) drought spread further north and east across Hidalgo County, with the western third of the county in Severe (D2) drought, the middle third of the county in moderate (D1) drought and the eastern third of the county abnormally dry (D0).  Beneficial rain during the second week of the month didnt improve drought conditions, rather drought conditions held steady.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Large hail caused an unknown amount of damage to vehicles, windows, and crops.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front stalled out over West Tennessee during the evening hours of September 2nd, 2014. As a result, showers and thunderstorms trained over the same area for a couple of hours. This caused flash flooding to occur over portions of the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Showers and thunderstorms trained over Northern Carroll County for a couple of hours. As a result, flash flooding occurred in a few locations between Trezevant and Huntingdon. The intersection of Highway 190 and Oak Grove Road in Trezevant had to be closed due to high water as well as the South Bypass around Huntingdon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving cold front moved into the Mid-South during the morning hours of September 11th, 2014. Showers and thunderstorms developed along the front and kept redeveloping over the same area due to a low level jet that was over the area. Southwest Tennessee and Extreme Northwest Mississippi was hit the hardest. Widespread 5-6 inches of rain fell over this particular area with scattered locations receiving as much as 7-10 inches of rain. Widespread flash flooding occurred and many roads had to be closed due to high water. Small rivers and streams overflowed their banks and in some instances locations that normally do not flood in heavy rain events did flood.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain produced flash flooding near Chisholm Lake. As a result, Chisholm Lake Road and the bridge near the lake were impassable due to high water.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An active monsoon pattern that characterized July 2014 continued into August, with an especially wet period during the first several days of the month. Widespread heavy rain eased from the 6th through 8th, however, as more typical isolated to scattered thunderstorms dominated the landscape from the 9th through 12th.  A monsoon burst, aided by a subtropical low pressure system aloft, brought heavy rain and local flash flooding on the 13th and 14th. Drier air worked into the northwest parts of the state with much less storm activity from the 15th into the 21st. Another good surge of monsoon moisture from the south arrived late on the 21st with widespread showers and storms on the 22nd, some with heavy rain and flash flooding. The 23rd was much drier then a gradual increase in moisture returned on the 24th and continued into the 27th. The 26th was an active day with a few reports of significant flash flooding. The remainder of the month turned much drier and warmer.  Despite the active monsoon,  New Mexico's rangeland and pastures were rated 56% very poor to poor at the beginning of the month,  with  only modest improvements during the month. Despite short-term gains,  longer-term hydrological impacts (below-normal reservoir levels) remained after multiple years of below-normal snowpack. The Middle Rio Grande Conservancy District curtailed water bank deliveries for irrigation in response to low flows along the Rio Grande during the month. The combination of short- and long-term hydrological impacts, below-normal mountain snowpack conditions in the headwater regions led to the re-introduction of an area of Moderate Drought (D1) in the Middle Rio Grande corridor from Socorro County northward to Sante Fe County.

September was a bit a mixed bag as far as rainfall west across South Central Texas. About half of the area had above normal precipitation and about half had less than normal. As a result none of our counties worsened during the month. Bandera, Gillespie, Kendall, Kerr, and Val Verde Counties improved to Severe Drought category (Stage D2). Medina County remain in Extreme Drought category (Stage D3) and Bexar, Blanco, Burnet, Comal, De Witt, Edwards, Llano, and Real Counties remained in Stage D2. Fire danger was moderate across the area at the end of September.  Of the counties in D2 or worse drought Bexar, Burnet, Comal, Kerr, De Witt, Medina, and Val Verde had burn bans remaining in effect. The seven day stream flow averages at the end of the month were below normal (10-24 percent) for the Middle San Antonio, Nueces, Medina, and Frio River basins. The Lower Colorado, the Upper, and the Lower San Antonio River Basins were much below normal (less than 10 percent). Area lakes and reservoirs continued well below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad had marked improvement was 33.9 feet below normal. Lake Travis was up slightly at 57.1 feet below normal. Medina Lake dropped again and was 88.3 feet below normal. The Edwards Aquifer rose a couple of feet during the month and was at 628.8 feet. This was 8.2 feet lower than at the end of September 2013 and 35 feet below average. The Edwards Aquifer Authority continued stage 4 water restrictions requiring large water users to reduce pumping by 40%. The Barton Springs Edwards Aquifer Conservation District declared stage 2 alarm drought status requiring a 20% reduction in pumping. San Marcos was in stage 4 water restrictions, Fredericksburg and New Braunfels were in stage 3, Kerrville, San Antonio Water System (SAWS), and Austin were in stage 2, and Del Rio and Seguin were in stage 1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Late in the afternoon of September 19th, scattered thunderstorms developed across southern Manitoba. These storms seemed to develop around a weak surface low that had lingered over the northern Red River Valley through the afternoon. One thunderstorm crossed into Pembina County in northeast North Dakota, and immediately showed tornadic tendencies. As this storm crossed into Kittson County in northwest Minnesota it produced a tornado. Other storms resulted in a second tornado as well as several reports of large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nickel to half dollar sized hail cracked the windshield and lights on a fire truck. The hail covered the ground, making it appear white.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered to numerous showers and thunderstorms developed during the late morning through the afternoon hours on September 2nd across extreme Eastern Texas, North Louisiana, and Southern Arkansas. A couple of these storms became severe during the afternoon, with an EF-1 tornado touching down northeast of Mansfield in Desoto Parish. This tornado snapped numerous trees just east of Clear Lake, where it crossed over the International Paper Plant, peeling back portions of the metal walls and roof. One car was flipped over, and numerous car windows were blown out as well at the IP Plant, as it tracked east into western Red River Parish. Several other trees were snapped across mainly open pasture, before the tornado crossed over Highway 1 and lifted prior to reaching the Red River. This parent thunderstorm re-intensified as it shifted northeast into southern Bienville Parish, where a large swath of 60+ mph winds blew across the western and central portions of the parish. This resulted in numerous trees being downed across the parish before weakening shortly there afterwards.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were downed in and around the community of Ringgold, Louisiana.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Late in the afternoon of September 19th, scattered thunderstorms developed across southern Manitoba. These storms seemed to develop around a weak surface low that had lingered over the northern Red River Valley through the afternoon. One thunderstorm crossed into Pembina County in northeast North Dakota, and immediately showed tornadic tendencies. As this storm crossed into Kittson County in northwest Minnesota it produced a tornado. Other storms resulted in a second tornado as well as several reports of large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Significant tree and property damage were reported.

Scattered to numerous showers and thunderstorms developed during the late morning through the afternoon hours on September 2nd across extreme Eastern Texas, North Louisiana, and Southern Arkansas. A couple of these storms became severe during the afternoon, with an EF-1 tornado touching down northeast of Mansfield in Desoto Parish. This tornado snapped numerous trees just east of Clear Lake, where it crossed over the International Paper Plant, peeling back portions of the metal walls and roof. One car was flipped over, and numerous car windows were blown out as well at the IP Plant, as it tracked east into western Red River Parish. Several other trees were snapped across mainly open pasture, before the tornado crossed over Highway 1 and lifted prior to reaching the Red River. This parent thunderstorm re-intensified as it shifted northeast into southern Bienville Parish, where a large swath of 60+ mph winds blew across the western and central portions of the parish. This resulted in numerous trees being downed across the parish before weakening shortly there afterwards.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were downed in the village of Jamestown, Louisiana.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: September was a bit a mixed bag as far as rainfall west across South Central Texas. About half of the area had above normal precipitation and about half had less than normal. As a result none of our counties worsened during the month. Bandera, Gillespie, Kendall, Kerr, and Val Verde Counties improved to Severe Drought category (Stage D2). Medina County remain in Extreme Drought category (Stage D3) and Bexar, Blanco, Burnet, Comal, De Witt, Edwards, Llano, and Real Counties remained in Stage D2. Fire danger was moderate across the area at the end of September.  Of the counties in D2 or worse drought Bexar, Burnet, Comal, Kerr, De Witt, Medina, and Val Verde had burn bans remaining in effect. The seven day stream flow averages at the end of the month were below normal (10-24 percent) for the Middle San Antonio, Nueces, Medina, and Frio River basins. The Lower Colorado, the Upper, and the Lower San Antonio River Basins were much below normal (less than 10 percent). Area lakes and reservoirs continued well below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad had marked improvement was 33.9 feet below normal. Lake Travis was up slightly at 57.1 feet below normal. Medina Lake dropped again and was 88.3 feet below normal. The Edwards Aquifer rose a couple of feet during the month and was at 628.8 feet. This was 8.2 feet lower than at the end of September 2013 and 35 feet below average. The Edwards Aquifer Authority continued stage 4 water restrictions requiring large water users to reduce pumping by 40%. The Barton Springs Edwards Aquifer Conservation District declared stage 2 alarm drought status requiring a 20% reduction in pumping. San Marcos was in stage 4 water restrictions, Fredericksburg and New Braunfels were in stage 3, Kerrville, San Antonio Water System (SAWS), and Austin were in stage 2, and Del Rio and Seguin were in stage 1.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust was measured via a home weather station.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: During the afternoon and evening of September 9, 2014 a line of thunderstorms moved though eastern Nebraska into Iowa and northern Missouri. Along the southwestern edge of the line a strong supercell formed, producing widespread wind and hail across far northwestern Missouri. This supercell went on to produce 5 brief and weak tornadoes across northwestern Missouri before finally dissipating. The main line of convection then caused wind damage across northern Missouri through the remainder of the overnight hours. Another tornado then formed early in the morning on September 10 near Kirksville, Missouri. This tornado moved into the town and caused some minor damage to trees and residences. Once the wind and tornado threat decreased widespread heavy rain, producing up to 10 inches in some areas, caused flooding and flash flooding across much of northern Missouri, including closures to several main highways. No injuries were reported as a result of the severe weather and flooding, but the far northern part of the state received much damage on account of the winds and flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Many streets in Tarkio had over a foot of water running over them. Highway AA north of Tarkio was also flooded by running water, caused by heavy rain.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Monsoon moisture generated thunderstorms that produced hail up to 1 inch in diameter, strong winds, and flash flooding in portions of central and northeast Nevada.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous roads showed evidence of flash flooding with damage to some of the roads along the Goshute mountains.  Rocks and mud were also washed onto  some of the roads. Damages are estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread heavy rains caused some minor flooding across portions of Southeast Kansas.  Some rainfall amounts accumulated to nearly 6 inches over a 24 hour period.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall report of 2.35 inches in a 24 hour period.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread heavy rains caused some minor flooding across portions of Southeast Kansas.  Some rainfall amounts accumulated to nearly 6 inches over a 24 hour period.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall report of 2.55 inches in a 24 hour period.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Over a foot of snow fell across the higher terrain of north-central Idaho as an upper level trough laden with Pacific moisture moved through.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Lost Trail Ski Resort measured a storm total snowfall of 13.5 in 13 hours and 34 minutes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High pressure over the area allowed for valley cold pools to develop and temperature inversions to strengthen. This aided the development of freezing fog that caused roadways and other surfaces to become icy across portions of western Montana. A fatality occurred near Bigfork because of both operator error and black ice.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The MT DOT reported that US-2 had fog and icy conditions from Columbia Falls to Marias Pass. A weather spotter reported a glaze of ice on US-2 between Hungry Horse and Bad Rock Canyon with freezing drizzle at 9:29 am MST on Jan. 19.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level jet stream combined with above normal Pacific moisture gave the right combination for heavy snowfall across the central Idaho mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Lolo Pass SNOTEL recorded 20 of total snowfall with 2.30 of snow water equivalent between Jan. 28-30. It reported heavy snowfall between 6 am and 1 pm PST on Jan. 29. The Dixie COOP reported a storm total snowfall of 14.4 with 0.92 liquid equivalent.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level jet stream combined with above normal Pacific moisture gave the right combination for heavy snowfall across the central Idaho mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Pierce observer reported a three day snowfall total of 16.5 with 2.26 of precipitation. The Crater Meadows SNOTEL located 25 miles east-northeast of Pierce measured 28 of total snowfall with 4.40 of snow water equivalent.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed in the afternoon hours and lingered into the evening across portions of southeast South Carolina. These thunderstorms developed along and just south of a nearly stationary front to the north and produced numerous lightning strikes and thunderstorm wind damage reports.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: South Carolina Highway Patrol reported a tree down and in the roadway on Jericho Road between Augusta Stage Coach Road and Collie Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Isolated to scattered thunderstorms developed in the afternoon hours across southeast South Carolina. These thunderstorms developed along and just ahead of a unseasonably strong cold front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Jasper County communications center reported one tree knocked down on Deerfield Road near Tillman.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Isolated to scattered thunderstorms developed in the afternoon hours across southeast South Carolina. These thunderstorms developed along and just ahead of a unseasonably strong cold front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A pine tree limb approximately ten inches in diameter and fourteen feet long broke off as a storm passed by just to the south. The limb came down on Weatherbark Circle off of Dorchester Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Isolated to scattered thunderstorms developed in the afternoon hours across southeast Georgia. These thunderstorms developed along and just ahead of a unseasonably strong cold front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Liberty County emergency manager reported a few large limbs down on Old Hines Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cluster of heavy rainfall producing thunderstorms anchored over much of Charleston County in the afternoon hours. These thunderstorms were nearly stationary as they developed just north of a stalled front extending out from a weak area of low pressure over south Georgia. Up to 8 inches of rain fell in some locations in only a few hours, producing flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Folly Beach police dispatch reported a roadway closed due to flooding at the intersection of Center Street and West Arctic Avenue. There were also other reports of flash flooding in the downtown Folly Beach area including flood waters entering several businesses in the Center Street area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered convection developed during the afternoon hours across southern Georgia and northwest Florida with a moist and unstable airmass in place.  A few storms became severe.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down on a power line on Skipper Bridge Road east of Staten Road.  This report was relayed via Twitter from WALB-TV.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An approaching cold front, combined with tropical moisture in advance of Hurricane Arthur, produced two rounds of showers and thunderstorms during the afternoon and evening. The storms produced wind damage across much of the Bay State, primarily along and north of the Mass Pike.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was downed onto a house on Crescent Street which damaged the windows. Another tree was downed on Wellesley Avenue. A large limb was downed on Weston Road and wires were downed on College Road.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were downed on West Road in Goshen, on Goshen and Petticoat Roads in Williamsburg, and on Florence Road in Northampton.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving frontal boundary, combined with plenty of heat and humidity, led to the development of showers and thunderstorms during the evening. Some of the storms produced torrential rainfall which led to flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Keene, flash flooding made Woodland Avenue impassable, and flooding extended into one home. In Winchester, Route 119 by the covered bridge was closed due to flooding, and one side of the road was partially washed out. Old Westport Road was also flooded.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding washed out portions of Hodgen Road, Center Road, and Abijah Road in North Weare. A spotter reported 2.95 inches of rain in a short time.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Showers and thunderstorms developed during the morning and again in the afternoon as a slow moving frontal boundary crossed southern New England. A tropical airmass was in place which led to torrential rainfall and flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was struck by lightning on Locust Street in Swansea, which caused downed wires.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Showers and thunderstorms developed during the morning as a slow moving frontal boundary crossed southern New England. A tropical airmass was in place which led to torrential rainfall and flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding affected several streets including Narragansett Avenue, Southwest Avenue along the seawall, Shoreby Hill, and Jamestown Shores.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding affected parts of the downtown Warren area. Route 136 was flooded with at least one foot of water.

CZ_NAME: EDISTO BEACH SC TO SAVANNAH GA OUT 20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers and thunderstorms developed across the Atlantic coastal waters in the afternoon hours. With a light wind field in place, the environment was supportive of water spouts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A water spout was reported by a Hilton Head Island lifeguard near Sea Pines.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Showers and thunderstorms developed during the morning and again in the afternoon as a slow moving frontal boundary crossed southern New England. A tropical airmass was in place which led to torrential rainfall and flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Torrential rainfall produced significant urban flash flooding. In Waltham, the downtown area was flooded with many cars stranded, including Second Street, Cabot Street, Prospect Street, and Bacon Street. All eight lanes of Route 128 were flooded and impassable near Route 20, which led to gridlock for a few hours until the flood waters receded.  In Arlington, there were several road closures due to flooding in the area of Mystic Street and the Mystic Valley Parkway. In Lexington, Woburn Street and Massachusetts Avenue were flooded and closed. In Watertown, parts of Mount Auburn Street were flooded. In Medford, the area near Medford Square was flooded with water up to the engine blocks of cars.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: One severe thunderstorm developed along a differential heating boundary between cloud cover to the northwest and mostly sunny skies to the southeast. Lapse rates were steep enough for unusually large hail to fall in the Hosford area for the month of August.  This was only the 4th case of golf ball size or larger hail falling in the WFO Tallahassee county warning area during the month of August since 1955.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple trees were blown down in the Hosford area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The tornado destroyed a carport at one house. The trestles were also cracked inside of the garage. A utility pole was bent back (leaning) which was being supported by a digger. The garbage can was found in the trees; the trees were damaged. Several shingles were ripped from roofs.  A road sign and several more trees were also damaged nearby.  At the local Eagle's Club, siding was peeled back on one corner with branches strewn across the property.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado destroyed a carport at one house. The trestles were also cracked inside of the garage. A utility pole was bent back (leaning) which was being supported by a digger. The garbage can was found in the trees; the trees were damaged. Several shingles were ripped from roofs.  A road sign and several more trees were also damaged nearby.  At the local Eagle's Club, siding was peeled back on one corner with branches strewn across the property.  Estimated peak wind speeds of 75 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong northwest flow aloft was present across the Southern Plains and Lower Mississippi valley during this period. A disturbance moved southward out of this flow into the Four State Region. Strong mid level lapse rates and elevated instability resulted in the development of strong to severe thunderstorms during the predawn hours of October 6th. The storms eventually developed into a Mesoscale Convective Complex producing large hail and widespread wind damage across portions of Southeast Oklahoma, Southwest Arkansas as well as Northeast Texas and Northwest Louisiana.

A weak cold front moved slowly into McCurtain County, Oklahoma during the late night hours of October 10th and the predawn hours of October 11th.  Convergence was weak along the frontal boundary but was significant enough for the development of showers and thunderstorms along the front.  An isolated severe thunderstorm developed southwest of Idabel, Oklahoma producing strong wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Measured wind gust came from the Oklahoma Mesonet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front was situated west to east across Northeast Texas, extreme Northern Louisiana and Southwest Arkansas during the late afternoon hours of October 12th.  This warm front was moving northward ahead of increasing southwesterly flow aloft in advance of a strong upper level trough that began to effect the region on October 13th.  The warm sector south of the returning warm front the afternoon and evening of the 12th became moderately unstable and was uncapped.  Widely scattered strong to severe thunderstorms developed during this time period which resulted in strong and damaging wind gusts along with large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees were reported to be downed just northwest of Many, Louisiana.

CZ_NAME: FERNANDINA BEACH TO ST AUGUSTINE FL OUT 20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong pre-frontal squall line crossed the area late morning through mid afternoon. Strong wind shear and helicity promoted rotation cells as well as bowing line segments. One comma-head storm formed along the Interstate 10 corridor near Live Oak, and this cell raced eastward toward Jacksonville. The storm had a long-lived mesocylone, and the rear flank downdraft descended downward several times causing brief periods of strong low level rotation which caused a few tornado touchdowns. The RFD produced strong winds of 50-80 mph and caused widespread tree damage and some structural damage as the comma-head raced across north Florida, including the Jacksonville metro area.
Pre-frontal storms fired across southeast Georgia within the warm sector of an approaching cold front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A funnel cloud was spotted over Highway 441.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reported penny sized hail in Cherry Branch.

Numerous showers and thunderstorms developed during the afternoon and evening hours of July 28th, 2014. Several storms became severe producing strong winds and very large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The ASOS at Michael J. Smith airport in Beaufort reported a 37 knot marine thunderstorm wind gust.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: WeatherFlow site in the Pamlico Sound observed a 62 knot marine thunderstorm wind gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong winter storm brought rain, followed by freezing rain, sleet and snow to portions of western and north central Nebraska. The storm began as rain early in the afternoon on December 14th, and transitioned to freezing rain, sleet, then snow, during the overnight hours and daytime hours on December 15th.  The heaviest snowfall amounts ranged from 4 to 9 inches across north central Nebraska. Freezing rain and sleet caused additional impacts across eastern portions of north central Nebraska, causing very icy roadways.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: General public located 7 miles north of O'Neill reported 6 inches of snowfall. Snowfall amounts across Holt County ranged from 4 to 7 inches. North winds of 20 to 30 mph increased to 25 to 35 mph with gusts to 45 mph caused blowing and drifting with low visibility during the overnight hours into the daytime hours on December 15th. In addition, law enforcement reported icy roads and blowing snow on local roadways.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A winter storm brought heavy snow with blowing and drifting to portions of Sheridan County on December 22-23, 2014.  The highest snowfall totals were across northwest Sheridan County ranging from 12 inches near Hayes Springs and 6 inches near Rushville.  Across the remainder of the county, amounts ranged from 2 to 4 inches. Northwest winds increasing to 20 to 30 mph on December 23rd, caused blowing and drifting snow and visibilities as low as a quarter mile at times during the morning hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Law enforcement in Rushville reported 6 inches of snowfall.  Visibility was low, ranging from a quarter to half mile along with blowing and drifting during the morning hours on December 23rd.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An intense low pressure that passed east of New Jersey on the 2nd combined with an approaching high pressure system to bring strong northwest winds into Eastern Pennsylvania mainly during the late morning and early afternoon of the 2nd. Peak wind gusts averaged 45 to 50 mph. The strong winds knocked down weak trees, tree limbs and wires and caused scattered power outages. This was particularly true in southeast Pennsylvania where many trees still had leaves on them as October was unseasonably warm.  In Delaware County, a shed was tossed in Media and two vehicles were damaged by a downed tree in Havertown.  In Philadelphia, newspaper dispensers were knocked over. About 22,600 homes and businesses lost power, 20,000 in PECO Energy's service area in southeastern Pennsylvania.  Most of the outages were in Delaware and Montgomery Counties. The majority of customers had service restored the evening of the 2nd. The strong winds also caused arrival delays of about 90 minutes at Philadelphia International Airport. ||Peak wind gusts included 50 mph in Bushkill Township (Northampton County),  49 mph in Lenhartsville (Berks County), 48 mph at the Philadelphia International Airport,  47 mph in Mount Pocono (Monroe County), 45 mph in West Chester (Chester County), 44 mph in Perkasie (Bucks County), 43 mph in Pottstown (Montgomery County) and 41 mph at the Lehigh Valley International Airport.  ||A developing low pressure over the Carolinas moved offshore on the morning of November 1st. As it passed east of Cape Hatteras, North Carolina during the early evening of November 1st, the pressure gradient (difference) between it and a high pressure system in the Mississippi Valley started to increase and winds became stronger. This pressure difference over Eastern Pennsylvania maximized during the late morning of the 2nd. At 7 a.m. EST on November 2nd, the low pressure system was well east of the New Jersey coast and as it reached the coastal waters east of Massachusetts that afternoon, strong winds ceased across Eastern Pennsylvania.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers and thunderstorms developed during the morning hours across south central Arizona on October 9th, and due to an influx of tropical moisture from former tropical storm Simon, the storms were able to produce very heavy rainfall. Peak rain rates with the stronger thunderstorms approached 2 inches per hour, and the heavy rain led to significant flooding of roads and washes across the far eastern portion of the greater Phoenix metropolitan area, including communities such as Apache Junction and east Mesa. Flooding was reported along the Superstition Freeway in Apache Junction and this led to the issuance of an Areal Flood Warning which ran from 851MST through 1145MST.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers and thunderstorms developed across the far eastern portion of the greater Phoenix metropolitan area during the early morning hours on October 9th, and they persisted into the middle of the morning. Due to an influx of tropical moisture from former tropical storm Simon, the storms produced very heavy rain with peak rain rates approaching 2 inches per hour. The heavy rain led to significant urban and small stream flooding  across portions of east Mesa and Apache Junction, especially along the Superstition Freeway. According to a trained spotter located 1 mile southeast of Apache Junction, at 0816MST there was water 5 inches deep flooding the intersection of the Superstition Freeway US 60 and Tomahawk road in Apache Junction. Flooding was also reported along a wash extending from the intersection of Ironwood Drive and 16th Avenue to the Superstition Freeway near Meridian Avenue. As a result of the flooding, an Areal Flood Warning was issued at 0850MST and it continued through 1145MST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large regional severe weather outbreak affected the Tennessee and lower Mississippi Valleys with a mixture of isolated supercells and multicell line segments impacting Middle Tennessee. One supercell thunderstorm moved rapidly northeast across northwest Perry, Humphreys, eastern Houston, and Montgomery Counties, bringing numerous reports of large hail, wind damage, and one EF1 tornado. Other strong to severe thunderstorms brought wind damage and flash flooding to much of the rest of Middle Tennessee.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Large tree limbs were blown down on Tyree Springs Road between White House and Hendersonville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Weak disturbances moved across the region in association with a stationary front stalled across the area. Energy from these disturbances combined with heating of the day helped to prompted some showers and storms. One of these storms reached severe levels and produced penny size hail and caused wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail ranging in size from peas to pennies fell in the 100 block of Beaumont Drive.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system developed over the northern Gulf of Mexico and intensified as it headed toward the northeast U.S. A coastal low developed along the Atlantic seaboard on November 26th. This system spread snow, heavy at times, into northeast Pennsylvania during the late morning and afternoon hours of Wednesday, November 26th. The highest snowfall total of 10.2 inches was reported in Wyoming County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts ranged from 6-9 inches across the county. The highest amount of 9.2 inches fell in Clarks Summit.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moving up the east coast brought a soaking rain and strong winds to much of southern New England.  The strongest winds were along the east coast of Massachusetts where many trees were still fully leaved.  This resulted in significant tree damage along with power outages.  In addition, both downed leaves from the storm and naturally fallen leaves from before the storm clogged storm drains which resulted in street flooding, particularly across northeastern Massachusetts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was downed on Center Street in Raynham. In Taunton, a tree and wires were downed onto a house on Danforth Street.  A large branch was blocking the ramp from Route 24 to Route 140.  A limb was downed onto wires on Peckham Road in Acushnet.  A large tree was downed onto Main Street at the Acushnet Rochester line blocking the northbound side of the road.  In Attleboro, a tree was downed blocking Steere Street.  Trees and wires were downed onto a car on Park Street at Wilmarth Street.  A tree was downed on Elm Street in Mansfield.
